name: Radhe
desc: This is definitely not the most wanted Bhai film, but the die-hard Salman fans might just find a reason to cheer him on, yet again.

name: 99 Songs
desc: A budding musician takes up the challenge to compose one song that can change the world, to unite with his girlfriend.

name: Bansuri: The Flute
desc: In a nutshell, ‘Bansuri’ has its heart at the right place, however, it fails to leave a lasting impact on the audience. Truth be told, even the sincere performances couldn’t cause us to hear the strains of the flute till far.

name: The Big Bull
desc: Overall, ‘The Big Bull’ is a decent attempt to tell a dramatic story of one of India’s biggest financial scams, orchestrated by a man, who seemed more like a common man than a con man. Watch it if you’re an Abhishek Bachchan fan, but don’t let the stock of your expectations rise too high.

name: Koi Jaane Na
desc: The most convincing part about this one is its title ‘Koi Jaane Na’ that perfectly sums up the feeling after watching it.

name: Flight
desc: ‘Flight’ circles around the systematic abuse of money and power the aviation-manufacturing industry is allegedly plagued with but from the way this tale’s shaped up to the way the makers have executed it on screen, we would say it shouldn’t have left the runway in the first place.

name: Saina
desc: The film follows the career highs and lows of the former world no 1, India’s ace shuttler, Saina Nehwal. It also pays tribute to the people who immensely contribute to her resilience and unbreakable spirit.

name: Sandeep Aur Pinky Faraar
desc: ‘Sandeep and Pinky Faraar’ is one of those neo-noir films that set out with a promise to engage, entertain and educate by slowly unraveling its layered subtext. But with its preposterous execution and frustratingly slow pace, it’s the audience who might want to escape, much before Sandeep and Pinky.

name: Time To Dance
desc: For its 113 minutes’ runtime, ' Time To Dance' offers a bucketful of superb dance performances to keep you engaged throughout.

name: Roohi
desc: Overall, the film remains true to its genre and packs a good dose of entertainment, which makes it worth a trip to the theatre.

name: Tuesdays & Fridays
desc: Overall, it’s a novel idea with a fresh and breezy storyline that has its moments. But with more depth and soul, this idea of bi-weekly romance could have become a love story for all seasons.

name: Maassab
desc: Overall, ‘Maassab’ deals with the issue of the dilapidated condition of rural education in India that needs special attention from the government. Despite a convincing and impactful story in hand, this social commentary turns out to be an average watch.

name: Madam Chief Minister
desc: Madam Chief Minister gets our vote for being an entertaining political drama, set in the crime-infested corridors of power.

name: The Power
desc: With a tighter, finer screenplay and more consistent performers, ‘The Power’ could have been a befitting response of this decade to the ‘Sarkar’ franchise but a lacklustre narrative, among other things, brings the power down to level zero.

name: 12 'O' Clock
desc: If you get spooked easily, you may not mind this one. However, as a psychological thriller that's focussed on ‘one’s believes in supernatural activities only when they have faced themselves’, ’12 ‘o' Clock’ fails to hold your attention for too long and ends up being a bit of a drag.

name: Kaagaz
desc: To sum it up, ‘Kaagaz’ could have been the go-to movie for those seeking a burst of inspiration, but it ends up being a uni-dimensional masterclass on one man’s acting prowess.

name: Ramprasad Ki Tehrvi
desc: Despite all the good intentions and a talented cast, ‘Ramprasad Ki Tehrvi’ fails to make the desired impact and eventually turns out to be an average family entertainer.

name: Coolie No. 1
desc: The film’s music is catchy and the songs are well-shot with all the shenanigans of a grand Bollywood potboiler in place. It makes for a good watch, but the ‘Mirchi lagi’ song deserved a much better remake. Oh, and that’s true for the film as well.

name: Shakeela
desc: Overall, ‘Shakeela’ is an honest attempt that tells a much lesser known story of a fallen star, but more conviction and stronger writing, could have propelled this not-so-dirty picture to newer highs.

name: Torbaaz
desc: Torbaaz is a Hindi movie released on 11 Dec, 2020. The movie is directed by Girish Malik and  featured Sanjay Dutt, nargis fakhri, ankita lokhande and Rahul Dev as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Torbaaz are Jay Patel and Rahul Mittra

name: Indoo Ki Jawani
desc: Logic is often scarified at the altar of comedy and entertainment, but the problem with writer-director Abir Sengupta’s story is that it’s highly preposterous and profoundly silly.

name: Durgamati
desc: In a world where politics is synonymous to hooliganism to some and egalitarianism is an alien concept (again, to some), ‘Durgamati’ does have a lesson or two to impart but the narrative and its storytelling technique is so bland that it slips through the cracks.

name: Darbaan
desc: Darbaan is a Hindi movie released on 4 Dec, 2020. The movie is directed by Bipin Nadkarni and  featured Sharib Hashmi, Sharad Kelkar, Rasika Dugal and Flora Saini as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for Darbaan is and Harsh Chhaya

name: Sir
desc: Tillotama Shome and Vivek Gomber are outstanding as two people who must reveal and conceal what they feel. To strike a balance between expression and refrain, innocence and courage — Ratna and Ashwin are tricky characters to portray.

name: Chhalaang
desc: On the whole, director Hansal Mehta gets the setting quite right with a lot of detailing. But with more conviction in execution and writing, this one could've hit it out of the park.

name: Suraj Pe Mangal Bhari
desc: Suraj Pe Mangal Bhari is a Hindi movie released on 15 Nov, 2020. The movie is directed by Abhishek Sharma and  featured Manoj Bajpayee, Diljit Dosanjh, Fatima Sana Sheikh and Annu Kapoor as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Suraj Pe Mangal Bhari are Supriya Pilgaonkar, Seema Pahwa, Manoj Pahwa, Neeraj Sood and neha pendse

name: Ludo
desc: Ludo is a Hindi movie released on 12 Nov, 2020. The movie is directed by Anurag Basu and  featured Abhishek Bachchan, Rajkummar Rao, Aditya Roy Kapur and Pankaj Tripathi as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Ludo are Sanya Malhotra, Fatima Sana Sheikh, Rohit Saraf, Pearle Maaney and Asha Negi

name: Laxmii
desc: The project is ambitious and has cherry-picked an interesting angle to inculcate into the narrative – of the ghost being a transgender with unfinished business – but the execution is over the top and melodramatic even by comedy standards.

name: Khaali Peeli
desc: In a nutshell, ‘Khaali Peeli’ has slow-mos and a background score that is faster than the heartbeat of an average young adult and on top of everything, a hot pair leading the show! But it derails every once in a while and you wonder – quite empathetically – why! Then again, if you are missing your regular dose of the larger-than-life heroes on celluloid, ‘Khaali Peeli’ is the turn you take – samajla na?

name: Dolly Kitty Aur Woh Chamakte Sitare
desc: Dolly Kitty Aur Woh Chamakte Sitare is a Hindi movie released on 18 Sep, 2020. The movie is directed by Alankrita Shrivastava and  featured Konkona Sen Sharma, Bhumi Pednekar, Vikrant Massey and Amol Parashar as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Dolly Kitty Aur Woh Chamakte Sitare are Aamir Bashir, Neelima Azim and Kubbra Sait

name: Khuda Haafiz
desc: ‘Khuda Haafiz’ does not have the most innovative script on the planet but it still could have worked had it not been for the randomness in the second half and the outrageously sham Arabic accents.

name: Gunjan Saxena: The Kargil Girl
desc: More than anything else, Gunjan Saxena: The Kargil Girl is a deeply moving tale of a feminist father and his feisty daughter. It wages war against patriarchal mind-set and discrimination, and identifies it as a bigger threat to progress than the one we perhaps tackled in 1999.

name: Pareeksha - The Final Test
desc: The screenplay has noble intent at its heart but only manages to touch upon the periphery of the subject of the Indian education system and its shortcomings – an issue that required an in-depth handling.

name: Lootcase
desc: The plotline is intrigue personified; given. But, what it does lack is a stable momentum and subtexts that came off as fresh-from-the-oven ideas.

name: Raat Akeli Hai
desc: Raat Akeli Hai is a sincere attempt but it isn’t engaging enough for you to feel the joy of solving a murderous puzzle or detective riddles.

name: Shakuntala Devi
desc: Vidya Balan gets under the skin of her character and simply aces it in the titular role – she gives an unrestrained performance as Shakuntala Devi from the 1950s to 2000s which is captivating to watch, as every stage of her life unfolds.

name: Dil Bechara
desc: ‘Dil Bechara’ will always be remembered as Sushant Singh Rajput’s swan song. Watch this movie simply to witness Sushant Singh Rajput’s last act. A brilliant one at that.

name: Virgin Bhanupriya
desc: Bhanupriya is a young girl hailing from a conservative family who claims to have experienced everything in life except sex. After multiple failed attempts at losing her virginity and a fortune-teller’s prediction that she will remain a virgin all her life, Bhanupriya decides to tie the knot, hoping that marriage will change things for the better.

name: Gulabo Sitabo
desc: In Bollywood, we don’t see too many intelligently made satires but this one … navigates that genre with tact and skill, with a climax that’s surprising, dark and humourous.

name: Angrezi Medium
desc: There are some fantastic moments in the film, and sharply written scenes between the characters, too, which in turn, prove to be  the highlights of this drama.

name: Har Kisse Ke Hisse: Kaamyaab
desc: ‘Kaamyaab’ is an ode to Bollywood, the larger-than-life movies and their actors, bizarre wigs, love, drama, friendship passion but most importantly, it is about one’s ability to realise their dreams even when the chips are down.

name: Guns Of Banaras
desc: What ‘Guns of Banaras’ primarily lacks is a convincing motive for the protagonist to sail through. So, save yourself from this unpleasant ride.

name: Cookie
desc: There was an attempt to do something 'hatke' with 'Cookie' but the diegesis is an amalgamation of all other movies in this genre; predictable till the credits roll.

name: O Pushpa I Hate Tears
desc: 'O Pushpa I Hate Tears' will remind one of yesteryear actor Rajesh Khanna’s famous dialogue which the movie's title is inspired from. But, sans that, there isn't much for the viewers... This Pushpa is passable!

name: Doordarshan
desc: Director Gagan Puri’s ‘Doordarshan’ had an interesting plot at hand and there was so much he could do with it, but he just about scratches the surface.

name: Thappad
desc: 'Thappad' is a silent slap on our society's age-old belief that — 'shaadi mein sab kuch chalta hain'. But honestly, should it be that way? And that is what we need to start talking about... now!

name: Shubh Mangal Zyada Saavdhan
desc: 'Shubh Mangal Zyada Saavdhan' will give small-town parents the much needed nudge, and maybe, in the distant future, they will have the strength to accept their offsprings for who they are.

name: Bhoot: Part One - The Haunted Ship
desc: While the film’s runtime is short, the pace seems exhausting because most of the scenes are concluded abruptly, leaving you waiting for the big reveal.

name: Love Aaj Kal
desc: 'Love Aaj Kal' sets off to celebrate complex characters and relationships, with the universal emotion of love at its core. It creates some emotional moments, but doesn’t quite leave you spellbound.

name: Hacked
desc: ‘Hacked’ feels like an exposé of some sorts at the beginning but gradually, one realises that it is just a half-baked attempt.

name: Shikara
desc: The narrative is a tad bit more visually exciting and cinematically engaging in the first half, while the second half is more invested in the love story – which does feel far-fetched, predictable and dated at times.

name: Yahan Sabhi Gyani Hain
desc: This comedy flick touches upon various alarming social issues, but fails to render an in-depth analysis on any of them.

name: Kaanchli Life In A Slough
desc: The predictability of the plot, a strong sense of directionlessness reeking of the plotline and its overall presentation makes this film a humdrum of an A-rated movie.

name: Taanashah
desc: Ritam Srivastav has done justice to the movie to a considerable extent but the script lacked originality in ways more than one.

name: Malang
desc: In this film, none of the characters are uni-dimensional, which makes them interesting. 'Malang' begins well with a power-packed action scene, and dives straight into the drama.

name: Jawaani Jaaneman
desc: 'Jawaani Jaaneman' comes out a winner with its non-judgmental approach and a contemporary story that showcases complex human relationships with all its quirks, firmly in place.

name: Gul Makai
desc: True, the subject of this biographical piece is fascinating but, H.E Amjad Khan’s take on the sudden upspring of insurgency and the Yousafzai scion’s subsequent victory does not translate onto the big screen.

name: Panga
desc: 'Panga' is a film that honours the endless hours of work that mothers put behind their families and at the same time urges them to never give up on their dreams.

name: Jai Mummy Di
desc: The story derails way before the interval and never gets back on track and there are way too many songs and dance numbers.

name: Bunker
desc: This war drama is one of those stories that has its heart in the right place, but fails to keep the promises that it makes.

name: Tanhaji: The Unsung Warrior
desc: 'Tanhaji: The Unsung Warrior' scores on various counts - superior performances, powerful action, visual impact, and most of all, it unfolds a story from the pages of history that deserved to be told, with just this kind of intensity, passion and vigour.

name: Darbar
desc: Looking at the flow of the script and the larger-than-life persona of Rajinikanth’s Arunachalam, it is safe to say that Murugadoss’s ‘Darbar’ is an ode to the veteran’s mammoth fan-base.

name: Chhapaak
desc: ‘Chhaapak’ is a sensitive film with a delicate, yet powerful, handling of a heinous crime against women, and an important story that needs to be heard.

name: Sab Kushal Mangal
desc: The film’s narrative makes half-hearted attempts at underlining social ills like forced marriages and dowry, but never really takes a solid stand.

name: Bhangra Paa Le
desc: Apart from the decent performances of its lead actors and a high-spirited soundtrack, ‘Bhangra Paa Le’ has nothing new to offer.

name: Good Newwz
desc: Through much of its runtime, director Raj Mehta ensures that 'Good Newwz' stays true to its genre with several light-hearted and funny moments. And the performances are top-notch, too.

name: Dabangg 3
desc: The film has all the ingredients required for a massy masala entertainer — good action, music, drama and, of course, Salman packing all of this in one story.

name: Unfriends
desc: Besides picking a subject that is socially relevant, no other aspect of this drama seems to be working in favour of the makers.

name: The Body
desc: This story does not bring anything new to the table as far as the thriller genre is concerned. Also, since it is confined within the walls of a mortuary and spans over a period of eight hours, this murder mystery tends to lose its grip over the audience early on.

name: Mudda 370 J&K
desc: Veteran actors like Raj Zutshi, Zarina Wahab, Pankaj Dheer and Hiten Tejwani try to save this murky rendering with some quality acting, but this period drama is beyond saving.

name: Mardaani 2
desc: It’s the conviction in the performances and a gripping narrative that ensure there’s never a dull moment in Mardaani 2.

name: Mamangam
desc: The very first element that ticks the right box in this film are the grand locations. The sets are spread over acres of land and special attention has been paid to the intricacies of the period setting.

name: Panipat
desc: ‘Panipat’ packs in a layered narrative that delves into the complex politics of the period, the intricate workings of war strategies versus might and the importance of forming alliances.

name: X Ray: The Inner Image
desc: The writers of ‘X Ray: The Inner Image’ – Ram Patil and Rajiv S. Ruia – do manage to concoct a reasonably gripping story that keeps you hooked for a decent amount of time. But the lengthy plotline compels the director to repeat some of the scenes and sequences, making it a tedious watch.

name: Yeh Saali Aashiqui
desc: The story navigates through various alleys, ranging from psychotic breakdowns to long-buried secrets, and even the subsequent vengeful tendencies, thus making it a delightful watch.

name: Tony
desc: 'Tony' as a psychological thriller, has its heart in the right place, but the execution could have been much better. The actors fail to do justice to this otherwise likeable story.

name: Commando 3
desc: Patriotic fervour captures almost every key scene in the film, but what manages to hold your interest is the tension and tact Vidyut Jammwal adds to every scene with his power-packed action moves.

name: Dosti Zindabad
desc: Angad (Rahuul Chwudhary), Sunny (Dev Sharma) and Abbas Khan (Ansh) -- mutually decide to part ways and then meet at the same place after a year, and see how their lives turn out during that time.

name: Pagalpanti
desc: Director Anees Bazmee, along with his co-writers, throw in everything into the mix. But nothing sticks, thanks to a weak script.

name: Keep Safe Distance
desc: The film packs several genres into one, including action, romance, drama, comedy and a whole lot of nationalistic fervour.

name: Marrne Bhi Do Yaaron
desc: The film’s screenplay is haphazard from the very first frame that goes on to prove that this comedy flick lacks the sharpness of a seasoned storyteller.

name: Marjaavaan
desc: Marjaavaan attempts to check all the boxes for an emotional action rollercoaster, but its dated execution doesn’t quite make the kill.

name: Bagpat Ka Dulha
desc: Right from direction and acting to screenplay and cinematography, nothing seems to be working in favour of this romantic comedy.

name: Satellite Shankar
desc: 'Satellite Shankar' attempts to tell the story of the sacrifices soldiers make while they fight for their countrymen, but resorts to every cliche and generalisation possible with a very weak narrative.

name: Housefull 4
desc: It's fourth edition the Housefull franchise ensures that it takes its brand of over the top, mindless humour forward. Actually, it's more like the reverse since it rewinds back six hundred years to the 15th century.

name: Made In China
desc: At the heart of it, Made in China carries the message of normalizing conversations around sex and exposing the taboo and hypocrisy surrounding it.

name: Saand Ki Aankh
desc: Bhumi and Taapsee are in great form as grandmothers. They carry the film on their shoulders effortlessly and indomitable spirit shines through even when the going gets tough.

name: Officer Arjun Singh IPS
desc: Despite a rather impactful storyline, the performances fall flat due to the weak dialogues and dated special effects. Even strong antagonists like Vijay Raaz and Govind Namdeo could not save the scenes.

name: Junction Varanasi
desc: It's a story of unbreakable bond between two brothers Amar and Prem – who are inseparable and can go to any extent for one another. Overall, it is a classic case of old wine served in a new bottle.

name: Ghost
desc: Ghost has nothing new to offer –in terms of storytelling, evoking fear or even making a feeble attempt in setting the bar high for Bollywood’s under-explored genre of horror.

name: Life Mein Time Nahi Hai Kisi Ko
desc: The filmmaker totally depends on actor Krishna Abhishek’s comic talent, but the problem is, the writing fails and the jokes fall flat.

name: Kirket
desc: It’s a pity that the execution is flawed considering a film on cricket has a lot of potential to do well in Bollywood.

name: Jacqueline I Am Coming
desc: ‘Jacqueline I Am Coming’ works and survives despite its lengthy narrative solely because of Raghubir Yadav’s heart-wrenching performance.

name: P Se Pyaar F Se Faraar
desc: The film straightaway jumps to the social issues it promises to bring to the forefront but, gradually starts introducing sub-themes and parallel characters that add very little or no value to the narrative.

name: The Sky Is Pink
desc: ‘The Sky is Pink’ is definitely a stirring watch as your heart goes out to the Chaudhary family and their zest for making every moment count, despite the trying times they go through.

name: War
desc: It’s a juicy proposition for fanboys and girls of both actors. A sort of millennial throwback to the 90s showdown between Sanjay Dutt and Jackie Shroff in Subhash Ghai's 'Khalnayak'.

name: Sye Raa Narasimha Reddy
desc: While the storytelling has its flaws, what needs to be lauded is that the makers pulled out this tale from the pages of history and mounted it on such a massive canvas for us to see.

name: Little Baby
desc: A new side of father-daughter relationship of today’s era where teenagers want to live their life on their own terms

name: Kandy Twist
desc: The film is evidently inspired from a lot of other movies from the crime genre and despite the stark similarities, ‘Kandy Twist: The Crime Story’ fails to pique the audience’s interest.

name: The Zoya Factor
desc: An adaptation of Anuja Chauhan’s novel by the same name, the vibe here is breezy and feel-good. Even some of the improbable moments are dealt with amusingly well.

name: Pal Pal Dil Ke Paas
desc: For a film aspiring to be an innocent love story, the chemistry between the lead pair isn’t exactly crackling to create any memorable moments.

name: Dream Girl
desc: Despite the flaws, ‘Dream Girl’ attempts to show the leading man in a different light, and manages to entertain in parts.

name: Pehlwaan
desc: Despite the direct mythological references from Lord Krishna’s life that lay the foundation of this family entertainer, ‘Pehlwaan’ fails to tick the right boxes.

name: Section 375
desc: ‘Section 375’ is an audacious effort. It is a relevant film that tackles a complex issue and one that will engage, inform and open up debates.

name: Mission Mangal
desc: Under the vision of creative director R Balki and an average execution by filmmaker Jagan Shakti, 'Mission Mangal' makes good with its emotional highs and drama.

name: Batla House
desc: Told through the eyes of an upright ACP, Sanjay Kumar (John Abraham), Nikkhil Advani’s ‘Batla House’ attempts to balance out the narrative without taking any apparent sides.

name: Mushkil
desc: Other than the six crucial characters in the film, the sound effects team deserves a special mention in this review, because without them, the supposedly ‘scary’ scenes are just laughable.

name: Pranaam
desc: Pranaam is a Hindi movie released on 9 Aug, 2019. The movie is directed by Sanjiv Jaiswal and  featured Rajeev Khandelwal, Sameksha Singh, Atul Kulkarni and Vikram Gokhale as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Pranaam are Abhimanyu Singh, Aniruddh Dave and Apoorva Arora

name: Jabariya Jodi
desc: Jabariya Jodi tries to throw light on serious issues with lighter moments, but gets tangled in a melodramatic and unrealistic narrative that doesn’t feel all that jabardust.

name: Chicken Curry Law
desc: ‘Chicken Curry Law’ is an attempt to start a dialogue and bring about a change, but if you’re looking for a story that leaves an impact, this one is far from that.

name: Khandaani Shafakhana
desc: While Khandaani Shafakhana’s intent is bang on, what it really needed was a heavier dose of humour and entertainment.

name: Arjun Patiala
desc: Spoof comedies can be a tricky affair and this one is way too underwhelming to tickle your funny bone for full two hours.

name: Judgementall Hai Kya
desc: 'Judgementall Hai Kya' keeps the element of suspense alive all the way till the end.The film pushes the envelope as a dark,psychological whodunit,with a social message weaved in that can’t be ignored.

name: Penalty
desc: It is refreshing to see someone making a full-flown feature film on Northeast-related problems but a fresh perspective, with tighter story-telling techniques and a better protagonist shouldering that kind of responsibility would have done the trick.

name: Jhootha Kahin Ka
desc: Much confusion ensues when best friends Varun and Karan swap identities hoping to carry on with their romances without any hitch.

name: Family Of Thakurganj
desc: Two brothers with different values - one takes the law into his hands, the other sibling is sincere and law-abiding. With different ideologies in life will they part ways or be together to fight against the injustice they suffer?

name: The Lion King
desc: For those who haven’t seen the original, 'The Lion King' (2019) is certainly worth a watch for its gorgeous visuals and technical genius.

name: Super 30
desc: ‘Super 30’ is a human drama and the story of a teacher who triumphs over the many challenges that life throws at him, to set an example for the world to see. Just for that it’s worth a watch.

name: Malaal
desc: Malaal is reminiscent of sweet romances when hand written notes were actually a thing and it’s tender moments like these that sets the film apart.

name: One Day: Justice Delivered
desc: It’s a story of a retired judge, who turns vigilante after retirement, to punish all those culprits who were walking the streets scot-free, owing to lack of evidence against them.

name: Hume Tumse Pyaar Kitna
desc: Hume Tumse Pyaar Kitna is a Hindi movie released on 5 Jul, 2019. The movie is directed by Lalit Mohan and  featured Karanvir Bohra, Priya Banerjee, Samir Kochhar and Mahesh Balraj as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for Hume Tumse Pyaar Kitna is and Bhavin Bhanushali

name: Marudhar Express
desc: The different facets of this movie may seem endearing, but the truth is that this slice-of-life drama does not fulfil the purpose it sets out to serve – that is to impart a deep lesson on life.

name: Article 15
desc: Anubhav Sinha’s 'Article 15' is designed like a crime thriller. What works for the film is that it’s thought provoking, hard hitting while unflinchingly bringing to light burning social issues.

name: The Great Indian Escape
desc: The escape plan by three IAF pilots in 1971 is a story that people need to know in order to understand the intensity of the situation during the war and the extent to which the armed forces had to go to to ensure the safety of its citizens.

name: Kabir Singh
desc: While Kabir Singh is a welcome change from stereotypical love stories, this kind of love affair needs some getting used to.

name: Fastey Fasaatey
desc: The story is predictable and the punchlines sound like extensions of some of the popular one-liners from other romcoms in the past; quite average.

name: Kissebaaz
desc: The script is haphazard and the writers have rambled quite a bit, and even after serving a 123 minutes long movie, the film leaves us with more questions than answers.

name: Rescue
desc: The thriller ‘Rescue’ is nothing but a series of bizarre scenes put together in a random order, and presented under this film title.

name: Bharat
desc: Bharat is well-intentioned, entertaining and doesn’t succumb to the trappings of commercial potboilers. The fact that it tries a bit too hard to prove that, is its problem.

name: Shuruaat Ka Twist
desc: An anthology of six short films that explore the theme of ‘twists’ in the narrative and its various interpretations.

name: Nakkash
desc: This drama on social issues ticks all the boxes of a progressive and offbeat movie, and one should give this ‘art film’ a try.

name: Yeh Hai India
desc: ‘Yeh Hai India’ has its heart in the right place but the way this story has been told and projected on the silver screen is too Utopian to say the least.

name: PM Narendra Modi
desc: The film chronicles Narendra Damodardas Modi’s life and events leading up to his swearing-in ceremony as the Prime Minister of India in 2014.

name: On The Ramp Never Ending Show
desc: ‘On The Ramp Never Ending Show’ touches upon the subject of glamour, pathos and personalities but lacks power-packed performances to hold the movie together.

name: Student Of The Year 2
desc: SOTY 2 doesn’t have that Ishq wala love, but there is ample dosti, high school drama and cool stuff to keep you going.

name: 1978 A Teen Night Out
desc: The horror flick, which is bizarre to the core and brings nothing new to the table, is dripped in mediocrity both in terms of the script and cinematography, and the overall performances by a bunch of highly enthusiastic (but average) actors.

name: Blank
desc: 'Blank' has a complex narrative but not every piece of the puzzle makes sense. There are too many loopholes in the writing and the character development.

name: Tarpan
desc: ‘Tarpan: The Salvation’ focuses on the ill-treatment of people on the basis of caste, among other factors, which is unfortunately still relevant but everything else about this social drama makes it a drag.

name: Kalank
desc: What’s fresh about 'Kalank' is the treatment. This period drama is mounted on a lavish scale and whether it's the sets or the costumes, everything about the film brings the grandeur alive.

name: Paharganj
desc: ‘Paharganj’ manages to showcase the world of drug cartels and the overall situation of the area in question, but the story has been dragged beyond a reasonable extent.

name: Blackboard Vs Whiteboard
desc: ‘Blackboard vs Whiteboard’ touches upon an alarming topic but its execution and introduction of various sub-plots, along with a lousy and yawn-worthy courtroom sequence, make it pointlessly mediocre.

name: Albert Pinto Ko Gussa Kyun Aata Hai?
No Fathers In Kashmir
desc: 'No Fathers In Kashmir' is not a light watch - it's a poignant tale that leaves you thinking about the half-widows and half-orphans, and many such untold stories.

name: Railway Raju
desc: There are few things in life that are not supposed to add up under any circumstances and ‘Railway Raju’ is one of them (in the world of cinema). Take a U turn…scoot!

name: Tennis Buddies
desc: Ranvir Shorey’s portrayal of a stern Faridabad based, venom-spitting father is apt to the T, and rendering some equally moving scenes and sequences is the very docile Anushka Singh (Divya Dutta). However, the central character – played by young Dakshata Patel – is a downer.

name: Notebook
desc: The highlights of 'Notebook' are the cinematography by Manoj Kumar Khatoi and the performances by Zaheer and Pranutan.

name: Gone Kesh
desc: Qasim Khallow’s film is a heartwarming tale of conquering fear, crushing societal standards of beauty and exploring the parent-child bond.

name: Photograph
desc: Photograph isn’t a perfect shot and is lured by exquisite nothingness but it’s intriguing and takes you back in time. Like love and life, it’s uncertain and hopeful.

name: Luka Chuppi
desc: 'Luka Chuppi' is a fun ride that never gets too preachy or uncomfortable for the family audience. It’s a clean entertainer with a message that’s not too loud, but clear, for sure.

name: GGBB: Goopi Gawaiya Bagha Bajaiya
desc: GGBB: Goopi Gawaiya Bagha Bajaiya is a Hindi movie released on 1 Mar, 2019. The movie is directed by Shilpa Ranade and  featured Rajeev Raj, Manish Bhawan, Shahanawaz Pradhan and Vishal Kumar as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for GGBB: Goopi Gawaiya Bagha Bajaiya is and Shailendra Pandey

name: Sonchiriya
desc: Gripping, tense and unpredictable, despite being a slow-burn western, Chaubey’s period thriller makes for a riveting watch.

name: Facebook Wala Pyar
desc: The plotline of ‘Facebook Wala Pyar’, just like its title, is stale and oh-so-predictable. The actors seem to have internalised the 90s idea of romance and refuse to let go off that even though the setting is new age.

name: Ek Ladki Ko Dekha Toh Aisa Laga
Mansukh Chaturvedi Ki Atmakatha
desc: The story is stale and bizarre at the same time, and struggles to make any sense after the first 15 minutes or so; ‘Mansukh Chaturvedi Ki Atmakatha’ is just one person rambling about random things.

name: Woh Jo Tha Ek Massiah Maulana Azad
desc: Undoubtedly, this period drama is extremely informative and shares the message that Maulana Azad believed in and stood by – unification of Indians regardless of what their faith is.

name: Rangeela Raja
desc: Perhaps in a different era and with a tighter script, ‘Rangeela Raja’ would have been able to entertain the single screen audience. But, in the current scenario, this tale of a philandering prince feels a little too jaded.

name: Fraud Saiyaan
desc: Regardless of whether you enjoy con-man stories or you’re a fan of Arshad’s comedic talents, ‘Fraud Saiyyan’ is not the kind of film that you should spend your time and effort on.

name: Evening Shadows
desc: The film starts on a high note, as the lead character makes a trip home to meet his parents for the holidays. But the promise of the subject is soon let down by the unabashed predictability of the script.
From black magic and reincarnation to paranormal elements and eternal love, the director of the movie, Shravan Kumar, seems to have tried it all but nothing really works.

name: 72 Hours: Martyr Who Never Died
desc: The intent behind making this movie is noble, but the execution needed more work. For example, there are too many random cuts in the movie and the fight scenes don’t always look authentic.

name: Uri: The Surgical Strike
desc: Uri: The Surgical Strike is a fitting tribute to the Indian Army conceptually but cinematically, it’s not a film without flaws.

name: Simmba
desc: Simmba is a potboiler that you expect it to be, where the good surely outweighs the bad. There are enough paisa vasool moments including the cameo by the original Singham, Ajay Devgn.

name: KGF
desc: While there is a sense of temporary closure in 'KGF: Chapter 1', one also leaves the hall yearning for more. KGF surely seems to have delivered what it set to achieve.

name: Zero
desc: At first go, 'Zero' makes you light and easy, which is good, but the problem is that it doesn’t really take you on that flight of entertainment, which you set out for.

name: PK Lele A Salesman
desc: ‘PK Lele A Salesman’ is all things mediocre—the story is stale, shoddy cinematography, followed by some lame acting and disgusting sexual innuendos.

name: The Dark Side Of Life: Mumbai City
desc: The incidents shown in this slice-of-life flick, which are supposedly grim and a reflection of how life looks like, does not resonate with the audience whatsoever.

name: Hotel Milan
desc: Other than the novelty of the central plot, nothing really works in favour of director Vishal Mishra’s ‘Hotel Milan’.

name: Pihu
desc: 'Pihu' has all the elements you'd expect from a film that can attain cult status. In all fairness, the story does throw up a few nail-biting moments, too.

name: Thugs Of Hindostan
desc: The grand canvas of 'Thugs of Hindostan' does hold sway in terms of the visual experience, but at the end, this one is all show and no substance.

name: Rashtraputra - The Commander Of Surgical Strikes
desc: Rashtraputra - The Commander Of Surgical Strikes is a Hindi movie released on 2 Nov, 2018. The movie is directed by Aazaad and  featured Aazaad,  Arun Govil, Ruhi Singh and Zakir Hussain as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Rashtraputra - The Commander Of Surgical Strikes are Manish Chaudhary, Rakesh Bedi, Achint Kaur, Raza Murad and Deepraj Rana,Vivek Vaswani

name: Jack & Dil
desc: Jack & Dil is a Hindi movie released on 2 Nov, 2018. The movie is directed by Sachin P. Karande and  featured Amit Sadh, Arbaaz khan, Evelyn Sharma and Sonal Chauhan as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for Jack & Dil is and Rajdeep Choudhury

name: Mausam Ikrar Ke Do Pal Pyar Ke
Chal Jaa Bapu
desc: While the idea of catching bootleggers heavily invested in the world of fake currency is a noble thought, one simply cannot ignore the senselessness and lazy writing of ‘Chal Jaa Bapu’.

name: The Journey Of Karma
desc: 'The Journey Of Karma' is largely a montage of cleavage shots, bathing scenes and truly cringe-evoking love making sequence with some actually decent urdu poetry thrown in.

name: Namaste England
desc: 'Namaste England' is shot in some beautiful locations across India and Europe, but the exotic setting is let down by the predictable and uninspired writing.

name: Badhaai Ho
desc: This dramedy, based on children feeling terribly embarrassed by the outcome of their parents’ mid-age romance; with outsiders joining in criticism, conveys some really progressive thoughts. The situational humour of 'Badhaai Ho' is complimented perfectly, by striking performances from Gajraj Rao, Neena Gupta and Ayushmann Khurrana.

name: Jalebi: The Everlasting Taste Of Love
Helicopter Eela
desc: Helicopter Eela is a fun ride that manages to land safely despite some turbulence. Watch this simple and endearing tale of motherly love with your mom in tow.

name: Loveyatri
desc: Although 'LoveYatri' lacks the gripping appeal of more contemporary romantic stories, it might be just enough to satiate die-hard romantics looking to revisit the love stories of the 90s.

name: Andhadhun
desc: Open to various interpretations and unpredictable from beginning to end, AndhaDhun is an engaging thriller that keeps you on your toes and leaves you guessing all the way.

name: III Smoking Barrels
desc: III Smoking Barrels is a Hindi movie released on 21 Sep, 2018. The movie is directed by Sanjib Dey and  featured Subrat Dutta, Indraneil Sengupta, Amrita Chattopadhyay and Mandakini Goswami as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for III Smoking Barrels are Shiny Gogoi, Siddharth Boro, Nalneesh and Niloy Sankar Gupta

name: Pakhi
desc: Goes without saying that this social drama was made with a noble intent, but director Sachin Gupta could have turned it into a hard-hitting film on this glaring issue had it not been for those novices of actors and a loosely written script.

name: Manto
desc: Watch the film for the director's flawless interweaving of Manto's poignant writing into her script and watch it for the words — spoken and unspoken.

name: Halkaa
desc: The film hopes to explore a rare and valid issue — an individual’s right to privacy and dignity. While the premise is interesting, good intentions don’t make for good movies and that’s the problem with Halkaa.

name: Gali Guleiyan
desc: Open to various interpretations, what strikes you the most about Gali Guleiyan is the way it portrays alarming psychological isolation and parent-child disconnect.

name: Stree
desc: Despite all its flaws and ambiguous ideas, Stree is still an entertaining film. This is an experimental comedy, that creates an eerie atmosphere and it manages to be funny and scary at the same time.

name: Karim Mohammed
desc: One of the flaws of this well-intended film is that it's painfully long and the execution doesn't quite have the flair and finesse required for a dramatic story like this.

name: Blue Jean Blues
desc: The central character of Kris, had a lot of scope but writing doesn't etch out anything worthy. The treatment of the subject and the cinematography of this film are both lacklustre, too.

name: Delhi 47 Km
desc: The film touches upon the alarming social issues of forced prostitution, among others, but it does not get to the bottom of any one issue.

name: Page 16
desc: The script of this supposed-horror thriller, has absolutely no thrill nor does the narrative have any chilling, paranormal activity.

name: The Redrum:  A Love Story
desc: There are way too many sub-plots and underlying themes in ‘ The Redrum - A Love Story’, none of which have been explored well and they make no contribution to moving the story forward.

name: Fanney Khan
desc: 'Fanney Khan' is a star studded musical that starts on a high note and has its moments of glory. Anil Kapoor with a knockout performance makes it worth a watch.

name: Mulk
desc: Mulk focusses on some hard-hitting and burning issues, and brings to fore the other faces of terrorism, which often gets brushed under the carpet.

name: Nawabzaade
desc: Nawabzaade’ is your run-of-the-mill romcom that brings absolutely nothing new to the table. The girl woos, the guys fight over her only to realise later that they’ve been played. And that's it.

name: Saheb, Biwi Aur Gangster 3
desc: With a screenplay that surprises and performances to match, the movie successfully takes the legacy forward with minor bumps on the way.

name: Dhadak
desc: With all its strengths and weaknesses, Dhadak attempts to highlight some shocking truths about our society and for that it makes a worthy watch.

name: Sarkaar Haazir Ho
desc: The performances by all actors involved aren’t satisfactory, the director is not able to execute his vision and the screenplay seems like it was written in a tearing hurry.

name: Soorma
desc: The movie is a story told with its heart in the right place, and on that count it scores. It shows you the reality, minus the goosebumps.

name: Race 3
desc: Race 3 just does not work up the feeling of suspense and intrigue that made the previous masala movies from the franchise a guilty pleasure.

name: Bhavesh Joshi Superhero
desc: Vikramaditya Motwane’s take on the superhero genre with gritty, realistic action and a masked vigilante’s story that hits close to home, is worth a look.

name: Veere Di Wedding
desc: 'Veere Di Wedding' will find an appeal with the younger generations who can relate to the discussions and dilemmas of these veeres.

name: Angrezi Mein Kehte Hain
desc: The film has an impactful start, the kind that makes you sit back and ponder. The content, at least for the first part, is very relatable and its execution shows the plight of any woman who suffers in silence in a loveless marriage. But the screenplay begins to go haywire after the interval.

name: Raazi
desc: A compelling cast led by Alia Bhatt is driven by Meghna Gulzar’s steady direction to ramp up the emotional tension in this strong dramatic thriller.

name: Tishnagi
desc: Tishnagi is a Hindi movie released on 4 May, 2018. The movie is directed by Sameer Khan and  featured Aryan Vaid, Rajpal Yadav, Qais Tanvee and Anushka Srivastava as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for Tishnagi is and Kaveri Priyam

name: Omerta
desc: Omerta does shake you up in parts, but as a whole, it does not leave you as emotionally shaken as a film like this should.

name: Daas Dev
desc: For those who are expecting a film like 'Hazaaron Khwaishein Aisi'. One of Sudhir Mishra’s earlier films which artfully combined politics and love, this contemporary take on Devdas will leave you wanting for more.

name: Beyond The Clouds
desc: Majid Majidi's take on redemption is fleshed out by strong performances to make the movie another notable entry in his filmography.

name: October
desc: Shoojit Sircar breathes life into every scene with his nuanced direction, though the story remains slow-paced. Varun Dhawan impresses with the finest performance of his career.

name: Baaghi 2
desc: With better editing and a taut screenplay this one could have packed a stronger punch. However, folks who enjoy mindless and impossible action could watch this film to kill time.

name: Baa Baaa Black Sheep
desc: It pains to see actors as brilliant as Anupam Kher, Annu Kapoor and Kay Kay Menon, being a part of this silly, loud and torturous comedy of errors that you care nothing about, eventually.

name: Raja Abroadiya
desc: Raja Abroadiya is a Hindi movie released on 16 Mar, 2018. The movie is directed by Lakhwinder Shabla and  featured Robin Sohi, Vaishnavi Patwardhan, Yograj Singh and Harry Verma as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for Raja Abroadiya is

name: Hate Story 4
desc: Hate Story 4 serves up a lot of twists and turns. But most of its clever story reveals are let down by the fact that there’s just too much erotica on offer.

name: Dil Juunglee
desc: Barring the earnest performances of the lead actors and the supporting cast, there’s absolutely nothing wild or memorable about Dil Juunglee.

name: 3 Storeys
desc: 3 Storeys cleverly demonstrates the art of skillfully telling a story wherein all the loose ends of a plot are tied together into a neat whole.

name: Hamne Gandhi Ko Maar Diya
desc: This social drama holds very little relevance in today's time when peaceful coexistence has become a thing of the past.

name: Veerey Ki Wedding
desc: 'Veerey Ki Wedding' is a comedy of errors that deserves to be skipped as the makers have erred every step of the way. Or, watch it at your own risk.

name: Pari
desc: Anushka’s strongest work as an actor-producer so far, Pari has the ability to redefine the genre as it’s refreshingly different, atmospheric and moody.

name: Welcome To New York
desc: The film must have sounded clever on paper as it doesn’t take itself too seriously and attempts to recreate the irreverent tonality, characteristic of the banter at award shows. However, it doesn’t always manage to hit the bull’s eye.

name: Sonu Ke Titu Ki Sweety
desc: Despite its misogynistic nature, Ranjan’s lighthearted approach to counter gender stereotypes in modern relationships makes his take fascinating.

name: Jaane Kyun De Yaaron
desc: A dreary, snail-paced ‘comedy’ film with a message that doesn’t deliver laughs nor does it manage to give any coherent message.

name: Aiyaary
desc: ‘Aiyaary’ has an intriguing storyline delivered with measured performances that make it a worthwhile watch, but those expecting the clever Neeraj Pandey twists will probably be left wanting more.

name: Kuldip Patwal: I Didn't Do It!
desc: It is a story that tries to take on the system by bringing to light its wrongdoings, but drowns in its own mediocrity instead.

name: Padmaavat
desc: ‘Padmaavat’ is an entertaining, large canvas experience, brought to life by strong performances combined with Sanjay Leela Bhansali’s stroke of visual brilliance.

name: Union Leader
desc: While the plot has a very humane touch to it and the characters reek of realism, the end would have made perfect sense had we all been living in a perfect world.

name: Nirdosh
desc: Despite the loopholes and some terrible acting, the first half of 'Nirdosh' is lot crispier than the stretched-beyond-imagination second half.

name: Vodka Diaries
desc: While the mystery should be intriguing in a suspense thriller, what remains a mystery is the lack of anything intriguing

name: Kaalakaandi
desc: Kaalakaandi is a Hindi movie released on 12 Jan, 2018. The movie is directed by Akshat Verma and  featured Saif Ali Khan,  Amyra Dastur,  Kunal Kapoor and  Vijay Raaz as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Kaalakaandi are  Shenaz Treasury,  Isha Talwar,  Akshay Oberoi and  Deepak Dobriyal

name: Mukkabaaz
desc: Politics of caste, sports and workplace, Mukkabaaz launches a scathing attack on the system and hypocrisies of our society with a blend of love & humour.

name: Haseena
desc: Haseena is a Hindi movie released on 01 September, 2017. The movie is directed by Vicky Ranawat  and featured Innayat Sharma and Mohit Kumar as lead characters.

name: Panchlait
desc: ‘Panchlait’ has its cinematography, acting and even costumes in place (given the era and rural setting) but the script is its own enemy.

name: Game Of Ayodhya
desc: The film sums up with a message that is relevant to today’s time. But, a lot more effort was required in the area of acting, cinematography, direction and screenplay to make this one watchable.

name: Tiger Zinda Hai
desc: A lot of sequences defy logic, but at the same time, there are many moments that will leave Salman Khan and action film fans impressed.

name: Monsoon Shootout
desc: Perhaps, this film makes for a one-time watch, if you are in the mood to indulge in a narrative that’s not run-of-the-mill.

name: Game Over
desc: This con-artist flick is a sum total of all other con-meets-scam movies that we have already seen; only that this one is dripped in mediocrity.

name: Viraam
desc: With insipid performances, a very slow pace and a plot that you can smell miles away, 'Viraam' could have been better if it avoided the clichéd treatment that is often given to Hindi films.

name: Tera Intezaar
desc: With weak performances, forced VFX and a badly structured script, 'Tera Intezaar' is a film where you will be waiting desperately for the end credits to roll.

name: Firangi
desc: The family film isn't really tacky or repulsive, it's outright boring and that's probably worse because it's not even unintentionally entertaining.

name: The Window
desc: The recurring theme in ‘The Window’ is a wholehearted writer’s plight in this unforgiving industry and the myth that pathos alone can bring out the artistic genius in a storyteller.

name: Julie 2
desc: Director must have wanted to make a film that tells the fictional tale of the rise of a female star in cinema, but midway he seems to have changed his mind and turned it into an erotic thriller.

name: An Insignificant Man
desc: The documentary follows Arvind Kejriwal and his newly formed political party as they start campaigning for the Delhi Legislative Assembly election and the struggles the party faces as it takes on Goliaths in the political arena.

name: Aksar 2
desc: Aksar 2 is a movie that begins well, but quickly crumbles to a point of no return. The climax is predictable and the narrative towards the end slackens with the inclusion of a song.

name: Kutumb The Family
desc: Kutumb The Family is a Hindi movie released on 26 May, 2017. The movie is directed by Amit Shree Yadav  and featured Rajpal Yadav and Alok Nath as lead characters.

name: The House Next Door
desc: The House Next Door is a Hindi movie released on 10 Nov, 2017. The movie is directed by U. Milind Rau and  featured Siddharth, Andrea Jeremiah and Atul Kulkarni as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for The House Next Door is

name: Qarib Qarib Singlle
desc: As long as you don’t expect fireworks, Parvathy and Irrfan make this an enjoyably sweet film that will leave you smiling.

name: Shaadi Mein Zaroor Aana
desc: Shaadi Mein Zaroor Aana is a Hindi movie released on 10 Nov, 2017. The movie is directed by Ratna Sinha and  featured Rajkummar Rao and Kriti Kharbanda as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for Shaadi Mein Zaroor Aana is

name: Narayan
desc: A potpourri of Salman Khan’s Sultan and Farhan Akhtar’s Bhaag Milkha Bhaag, with a bit of Brad Pitt’s Fight Club thrown in, Narayan is a repetitive script.

name: Ram Ratan
desc: Ram Ratan is a Hindi movie released on 3 Nov, 2017. The movie is directed by Govind Sakariya and  featured Daisy Shah,  Rajpal Yadav,  Mahesh Thakur and  Sudha Chandran as lead characters.Other popular actors who were roped in for Ram Ratan is and  Satish Kaushik

name: Rukh
desc: Rukh is a Hindi movie released on 27 October, 2017. The movie is directed by Atanu Mukherjee  and featured Manoj Bajpayee, Smita Tambe and Kumud Mishra as lead characters.

name: Secret Superstar
desc: Young Zaira aspires to be a singer but faces several restrictions from her conservative father until she meets a musician who can make her dreams come true.

name: Judwaa 2
desc: It’s basically innocent fun meant to pander to the child in you. Lame lyrics, loud gags and leggy lasses never really hurt anyone.

name: CRD
desc: A student rebels against his tyrannical, fascist theatre teacher and forms his own group of odd-ball actors to compete in a prestigious theatre competition.

name: Haseena Parkar
desc: This crime drama fails to offer an insight into Haseena’s life whatsoever as an individual, beyond her infamous identity as Dawood’s sister.

name: Bhoomi
desc: ​Watch Bhoomi for Dutt. He’s from that era of larger-than-life heroes who get you to applaud even when he turns a killing machine.

name: Newton
desc: A brilliantly acted, impeccably written, lovingly shot, humorous, yet poignant film that Indian audiences didn’t ask for, but need.

name: Patel Ki Punjabi Shaadi
desc: A Gujarati grocery store owner who hates Punjabis is horrified to have a typical, loud Punjabi family move in as his next door neighbour.

name: Daddy
desc: If you like crime drama, Daddy is bound to fuel your imagination. Gawli is a part of India’s crime-history. And this is the closest you will come to `encountering’ him.

name: Sameer
desc: Sameer is a proper edge-of-the-seat thriller, albeit with its flaws, but keeps you hooked till the very end with a very strong pay-off.

name: Shubh Mangal Saavdhan
desc: 'Shubh Mangal Saavdhan' has a talented and affable cast to keep you entertained long enough to make it worth the watch, and to ignore an anti-climax.

name: A Gentleman
desc: This lazily titled film is an improvement on the leave-your-brains-at-home genre that we have been (just as) lazily lapping up.

name: Qaidi Band
desc: Overall, this Qaidi Band means and plays well but lacks the spunk and spirit required to arouse sentiments - rebellious or patriotic.

name: Partition: 1947
desc: 'Partition: 1947’ runs the gamut of emotions at the end of the British colonial rule in India, making this a timely and riveting watch.

name: Lipstick Under My Burkha
desc: Alankrita Shrivastava skillfully tells stories of women who have to lie, cheat and hide to lead their authentic lives.

name: Guest Iin London
desc: Aryan and his wife are saddled with the responsibility of uninvited guests, who have a dozen desi quirks and no sense of boundaries

name: Ek Haseena Thi Ek Deewana Tha
desc: Ek Haseena Thi Ek Deewana Tha belongs to the nineties, which was a simpler time when audience may have bought such an absurdist premise

name: Tubelight
desc: Salman laughs and cries unselfconsciously, unraveling the lesser-seen side of his macho image. He cannot move mountains with his performance but he manages to keep the faith alive. Sohail is sincere. Zhu Zhu shows spunk and young Matin entertains. And, Om Puri reminds you of the mettle unsung heroes are made of.

name: G Kutta Se
desc: Set in Haryana, the film looks at the consequence of falling in love and the price some people are ready to pay, to preserve their ‘honour’.

name: Bank Chor
desc: It is too reminiscent of bank-heist movies of the past; there are even clear shoutouts to the Dhoom franchise. A better plan of action and a few dry runs with the script would have ensured a product to bank on.

name: The Wishing Tree
desc: There’s a lot for the little ones to enjoy and learn, but we just wish that the film had a stronger plot that were realized in a better way.

name: Dobaara: See your Evil
desc: Adapted from the Hollywood horror film Oculus (2014), Dobaara allows for some moments of fear, apprehension, dread and scare.

name: Hanuman Da' Damdaar
desc: A bit more damdaar script would give the grown-ups a chance to enjoy the film too. But for now, it’s only the kids who may end up having a good time.

name: Sargoshiyan
desc: The saving grace in Sargoshiyan is its intent to explain Kashmiriyat; a term most people are unfamiliar with, given the cacophony around the region.

name: Thodi Thodi Si Manmaaniyan
desc: Thodi Thodi Si Manmaaniyan is a super-generic flick about ‘rock’ musicians devoid of any real emotion, grit or struggle.

name: Jattu Engineer
direc: Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh Ji InsanActor
act: ['Sukhotam Insan', 'Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh Ji InsanDirector, ', 'Sukhotam Insan']

name: Half Girlfriend
desc: Half girlfriend or boyfriend is that person many of us have encountered on campus. However, do we really want to relive those memories? It depends entirely on the mood.

name: Sarkar 3
desc: Subhash Nagre or Sarkar (Amitabh Bachchan), the patriarch of the most powerful family of Maharashtra, continues to hold centre-stage because of his immense clout with the masses.

name: Noor
desc: Noor wants to get into issue-based journalism but hasn’t found a solution to her own issues yet. Between a flawed love life, a flailing career and daily struggles with weight, she finds her meaty story.

name: Blue Mountains
desc: So, full marks to ‘Blue Mountains’ for trying to portray a young boy dealing with depression. But have they been successful in making any meaningful impact?

name: Laali Ki Shaadi Mein Laddoo Deewana
desc: Laali Ki Shaadi Mein Laaddoo Deewana has to be some kind of a scientific experiment to study the frequency of fidgeting in a theatre seat.

name: Mukti Bhawan
desc: Rajiv accompanies his father to Mukti Bhawan, a temporary housing facility for the elderly who suspect that they will soon pass on.

name: Naam Shabana
desc: Shabana Khan (Taapsee) is the special agent who is entrusted the task of assassinating a deadly arms dealer(Prithviraj) by the Indian Intelligence Agencies.

name: Poorna
desc: 'Poorna' is not only motivational for young Indian women, but for anyone looking to scale great heights against all odds.

name: Mantra
desc: It's refreshing to see, that in a film only 90 minutes long, just how the director manages to narrate multiple stories in an effective and engaging manner.

name: Trapped
desc: Shaurya’ (Rajkummar Rao) must pluck up the ‘courage’ (pun intended) to stay alive after he accidentally locks himself up in his new rented apartment in a desolate Mumbai high-rise, for almost a week.

name: Badrinath Ki Dulhania
desc: Badrinath Ki Dulhania is a rucksack full of radioactive social issues handled cautiously with bedazzled Dharma gloves.

name: Commando 2: The Black Money Trail
desc: Vidyut Jammwal is a solid action star and his stunts are the only reason you manage to sit through this never-ending tale of 'catch-Vicky Chadda-if-you-can'.

name: Jeena Isi Ka Naam Hai
desc: A clear case of riding the wave of women-centric films, Jeena Isi Ka Naam Hai has an overly simplistic approach at dealing with serious issues that concern women.

name: Wedding Anniversary
desc: If you have issues in your love-life, visit a marriage counsellor. Wedding Anniversary will only add some phrases to your Hindi/ Urdu vocabulary.

name: Running Shaadi
desc: While there may not be much of a Shaadi, there's definitely a lot of fun running around that you may want to check out.

name: Irada
desc: The film's attempt to educate the audience on the perils of chemical contamination, reverse boring and groundwater pollution that is a harsh reality around urban townships is half-baked.

name: The Ghazi Attack
desc: This underwater thriller is worth a watch for sure. It leaves you in awe of the soldiers, who lay their lives for their country.

name: Hind Ka Napak Ko Jawab – MSG The Lionheart 2
direc: Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh Ji InsanActor
act: ['Bhushan Insaan', 'Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh Ji InsanDirector, ', 'Bhushan Insaan']

name: Jolly LLB 2
desc: Akshay changes shades from crooked to straight, like a chameleon. In top-form, he puts up a perfect display of a street-smart lawyer who hasn’t read legal tomes but who has instead picked up tips from courtroom corridors to become Jolly LLB.

name: Raees
desc: Shah Rukh Khan has never looked better; he’s full of fury and for once, isn’t spreading his arms, but breaking others’.

name: Majaz: Ae Gham-e-Dil Kya Karun
desc: The film is the real life story of famous Urdu Poet, Majaz — his rise to fame, his star-crossed love life and his downfall that led to an early, lonely death.

name: Aasra
desc: A true story of a social worker who wants to transform a Pune slum by building houses for people thru government's slum rehabilitation scheme (SRA).

name: Kahaani 2: Durga Rani Singh
desc: Kahaani 2, directed by Sujoy Ghosh after a gap of four years, is a whodunit that definitely serves up intrigue, but fails to keep a tight grip on proceedings throughout its duration.

name: Moh Maya Money
desc: As far as crime thrillers go, Moh Maya Money is a well made project, where the characters may be cheating each other, but you'll sure get your money's worth

name: Saansein: The Last Breath
desc: Saansein’s formula is not very different but it doesn’t fixate too much on erotic scenes. There is a horny ghost of a jilted lover though.

name: Force 2
desc: John Abraham is intense and impressive when he’s breaking jaws and lifting cars, Tahir Raj Bhasin (in an extension of his Mardaani role) is good and shows his vulnerable side. Sonakshi Sinha’s half-hearted performance, however, can be partly blamed on her annoyingly underwritten character.

name: Ishq Junoon: The Heat is On
desc: Ishq Junoon is a hybrid of the two, which exists in a very strange territory. But it’s more funny-strange than scary-strange.

name: Chaar Sahibzaade:The Rise Of Banda Singh Bahadur
Yeh Hai Lollipop
desc: Yeh Hai Lollipop, the title bearing no semblance to anything in the movie, is a mall-film which is a decade too late, considering the mall boom is not a new thing in India.

name: Mahayoddha Rama
desc: The film is narrated from the perspective of the antagonist Ravana, it shows how the demon-king tries to defeat Rama and hilariously fails every time.

name: My Father Iqbal
desc: My Father Iqbal can pass of as a story of any regular person caught in tumultuous times but the J&K setting makes it slightly more convincing.

name: Love Day - Pyaar Ka Din
desc: With peppy music, bearable visuals and a hackneyed story line, this is two hours plus of juvenile attempts at humour.

name: MSG The Warrior – Lion Heart
direc: Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh Ji InsanActor
act: ['Kainaat Insan', 'Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh Ji Insan', 'Kainaat Insan']

name: Mirzya
desc: Harshvardhan and Saiyami come from good acting stock. But they’re still rough around the edges. If you are drawn to stories that are high on aesthetics with lyrical narratives, Mirzya is a portrait that deserves a long look.

name: MS Dhoni: The Untold Story
desc: If you are a diehard fan of MS Dhoni and cricket (in that order), you are bound to love this film, which reveres its protagonist.

name: Wah Taj
desc: Wah Taj aims to put focus on the pitiable conditions of farmers and the devil-may-care approach of the government machinery.

name: Days Of Tafree
desc: The film revolves around the idiosyncrasies and friendship of four college friends and the girls they supposedly fancy.

name: Parched
desc: Parched takes you into a disturbing and thought-provoking territory. Even as it cleverly intertwines the stories of the three protagonists all of who have had a raw deal in life.

name: Pink
desc: Pink is a powerful statement on the existing feudal mindset of a majority of India, where men and women are judged by a different yardstick.

name: Baar Baar Dekho
desc: Jai Verma (Sidharth Malhotra), a mathematical genius, finds himself randomly travelling through time - (into the past and future) until he learns to value his present.

name: Dark Chocolate
desc: As the real-life story started to unfold last year, the world lapped up the salacious and sleazy tale of Indrani and Peter Mukerjea's involvement in killing Sheena.

name: Yea Toh Two Much Ho Gayaa
desc: Scenic locales, beautiful ladies, comedy and action; Yea Toh Too Much Ho Gayaa (YTTMHG) has everything that goes into making an entertainer.

name: Sunshine Music Tours And Travels
desc: Shailendra Singh pays tribute to his own baby, the annual 'Sunburn' festival here by stressing on it's popularity and aspirational value.

name: Missing On A Weekend
desc: Pitched as a thriller, the film opens as an attempt to shed light over crimes in Goa and takes a fictitious course soon after.

name: Rustom
desc: Though the climax has been smartly fictionalised, this courtroom drama is essentially based on the real life of Naval officer K M Nanavati, who in 1959, shot and killed his wife’s lover.

name: The Legend of Michael Mishra
desc: It looks like they wore their own clothes, wrote their own lines and danced the way they wanted to without an expert guiding them whatsoever.

name: Moods Of Crime
desc: Two psychology students in their tryst to explore social deviance lose themselves to the thrill of crime, but it's a tricky tale to tell.

name: Madaari
desc: Intriguingly stoic, a mysterious man (Irrfan as Nirmal Kumar) kidnaps the Home Minister's (Tushar Dalvi) son Rohan. Strangely, Nirmal doesn't ask for money. He demands that the Minister and his team must go looking for his missing son first in order to get Rohan back.

name: Great Grand Masti
desc: For those who have a taste in adult comedies, Great Grand Masti is a fun weekend watch and one of the better ones we've seen this year.

name: Shorgul
desc: The performances are earnest, especially Jimmy Sheirgill and Ashutosh Rana. You'll find yourself deeply engrossed in their war of words and clash of ideas.

name: Raman Raghav 2.0
desc: The biggest problem with Raman Raghav 2.0 is that it glorifies the gore. The climax monologue will run your patience thin.

name: Luv U Alia
desc: Sometimes original work is best left untampered. In no way are we suggesting that the Kannada movie of the same name was a work of genius. But when dubbed and re-released in Hindi, the results are dismal.

name: Junooniyat
desc: The only thing you take back from this film are the breath-taking visuals of the snow-capped Kashmir mountains captured in their entirety. For the rest, this one draws a huge blank.

name: Do Lafzon Ki Kahani
desc: The only portion that manages to impress is Hooda flexing his muscles in the boxing ring as a MMA fighter. We wish it would have taken precedence over the ineffective mushy love story.

name: Housefull 3
desc: If you have seen the two earlier installments of this franchise, you already know that is purely a 'leave-your-brains-behind' affair.

name: Project Marathwada
desc: The actors do a fine job of salvaging the situation. Be it Seema Biswas or Dalip Tahil, the film’s supporting cast shines. But mostly, the film rides on Om Puri’s shoulders.

name: Fredrick
desc: For those who survive, a dialogue from the film will resound - ‘Sometimes stupid things work’. Well, we daresay, they don’t.

name: Veerappan
desc: In all fairness, Sandeep brings Veerappan alive and the National Award winner Usha as Muthulakshmi is convincing. Though not in top form, RGV does redeem himself to some degree.

name: Chudail Story
desc: In this movie, there are scenes lifted straight from Conjuring, Vaastu Shastra and even from Ragini MMS 2. Skip this one. It will suck the love for horror films out of you.

name: Dear Dad
desc: Dear Dad deserves a watch simply for the profound point it makes about accepting people for who they are and loving them unconditionally.

name: Azhar
desc: Emraan bears no physical resemblance to Azharruddin. However his mannerisms—the blinking of his eyes and swagger add to a knockout performance. Watch Azhar for him.

name: Buddha In A Traffic Jam
desc: Quoting from the film, the best thing that can be said about Buddha in a Traffic Jam is that we love the ideas Vivek brings forth but we are not in love with them. It lacks outrage and treads familiar ground.

name: 1920 London
desc: From the first frame itself, you get a hint of how ridiculous this will turn out to be but you sit in the hope that probably there will at least be one good enough scene that will scare you.

name: One Night Stand
desc: Even with a compelling idea, One Night Stand remains singularly superficial. Jasmine and her writer Bhavani Iyer, manage to whip up only a half-baked, predictable plot ridden with clichés.

name: Nil Battey Sannata
desc: It does get preachy and you find yourself shifting in your seats a lot towards the final scene, but the movie wins you over with its innocence and simplicity.

name: Sardaar Gabbar Singh
desc: The movie puts you to sleep despite its loud execution with its yawn-worthy monotonous shenanigans. While the fans can still overlook it, the major drawback of the film is its length.

name: Ki & Ka
desc: Kareena is terrific, Arjun, endearing. But Balki’s writing is inconsistent. A few scenes leave you misty-eyed, but for the most part, the stock situations are banal.

name: Rocky Handsome
desc: The Hindi remake of a Korean film struggles to blend action and emotion. Its need to infuse drama kills the thrill of its sleek and ruthless action. The climax is stretched for way too long.

name: Mumbai Central
desc: Mumbai Central is like a stretched version of a crime patrol episode. You can predict the crime and the climax but watch it anyway.

name: Ek Yodha Shoorveer
desc: It could have been a masterpiece, but five later, the film feels dated. Watchable but never half as engaging as the original.

name: Global Baba
desc: Global Baba is subversive but doesn't have an inventive streak. It points out problems without delving deeper or providing a solution. This one is just old wine in an old bottle!

name: Murari: The Mad Gentleman
desc: Murari The Mad Gentleman doesn't deserve to be called a film. It is an amateurish compilation of bad screenplay, terrible dialogues and dreadful performances.

name: Tere Bin Laden: Dead or Alive
Aligarh
desc: Aligarh stays with you much after you see it, especially for Bajpayee and his nuanced portrayal of a man brutally put to shame by an intrusive and insensitive society.

name: Bollywood Diaries
desc: Bollywood Diaries is one of those rare films that you would want to invest in but the half-baked narrative is not successful in holding your attention.

name: Direct Ishq
desc: Despite having it all - romance, action, comedy, decent actors to convey those emotions, the film fails to hold your attention on various grounds.

name: Ishq Forever
desc: Despite the flaws, if the story of a good-looking couple stuck in romantic situations at picturesque locations excite you, you can give it a shot.

name: Sanam Re
desc: Unless you consider Himachal as your Sanam, this heartbreaking tale on sacrifice and unrequited love, loses its plot and purpose somewhere along the way, re.

name: Ghayal Once Again
desc: Despite the flaws, Sunny's idealistic film exudes the sincerity and unbreakable spirit of a common man. If you mess with us, "We will find you and we will punch you." Watch it.

name: BHK Bhalla@Halla.Kom
desc: Comedies are meant to break the monotony of your life. In this case, you would prefer your mundane life twice over than subject yourself to such stupidity.

name: Mastizaade
desc: Honestly, this film looks like a better version of last week’s Kyaa Kool Hain Hum 3 because it has Sunny instead of Mandana Karimi. Otherwise, it is just as blah.

name: Kyaa Kool Hain Hum 3
desc: Wish the makers, who have invested so much in locations and item songs, had invested in a tighter screenplay because India is ready for a smart sex comedy.

name: Airlift
desc: Airlift works because it conveys a time when armies will attack civilians - you're struck by how IS was born from the Iraqi army's core - and raises Bollywood's generic bar.

name: Jugni
desc: Despite its freshness, the film fails to create an impact. It is hard to be affected by it due to its lack of depth.

name: Chalk N Duster
desc: 'Chalk N Duster' has its heart in the right place. Made with an intention of showcasing the worms in the current education system, this film can be lauded to some degree.

name: Chauranga
desc: Despite being a well-intentioned story about the many 'isms' that plague India, the film’s narrative fails to explore the dynamics of hierarchy politics that is the heart of the issue.

name: Angry Indian Goddesses
desc: Pan Nalin gives India an unusual female buddy film that attempts to make a statement on the growing atrocities against women.

name: Tamasha
desc: Deepika and Ranbir convey their angst and passion so convincingly that you’re hooked. Except for the curiosity about them, the rest of the drama is 'oh,never-mind'.

name: Charlie Kay Chakkar Mein
desc: Naseeruddin's Shah clever (as always) acting, ably supported by Amit Sial and Anand Tiwari, makes this crime mystery gripping, despite the flaws.

name: Ranbanka
desc: What could have been a decent revenge drama gets marred by uninspiring (hero) & overdramatic (heroine & the villain) acting.

name: Yaara Silly Silly
desc: Yaara Silly Silly is sillier than it claims to be. Avoid it and spare yourself the challenge of surviving this vile affair.

name: Guddu Ki Gun
desc: The film can give terrible sex comedies a run for their money. Kunal Kemmu tries his best to make this dickfest watchable but it’s outright repulsive.

name: Titli
desc: Titli is not for the faint-hearted as it not only introduces you but makes you feel a part of the family that gives you the creeps.

name: Main Aur Charles
desc: Prawaal Raman does a commendable job of recreating the 60s-70s. He also gets his protagonist's physicality and smugness bang on.

name: Once Upon A Time In Bihar
desc: This one aspires to trigger a revolution by projecting its protagonists as crusaders of human rights. Sadly, all they do is preach and then commit an idiotic crime themselves.

name: Shaandaar
desc: In his attempt to spoof destination weddings of the bankrupt and the famous, Vikas Bahl,(who also directed that gem, Queen) forgot to take a script along.

name: Pyaar Ka Punchnama 2
desc: This film may resonate with some masochistic sorts who like taking a whipping in love. Or still others, who just enjoy a few laughs at the cinemas each week!

name: Jazbaa
desc: Jazbaa’s narrative has pace and power. From screeching car sequences to emotionally-charged showdowns between his accomplished lead cast; the film throbs.

name: Singh Is Bliing
desc: Don’t go expecting logic in the story, as this is a quirky comedy that solely relies on superstar Akshay’s swag to keep you entertained.

name: Puli
desc: Puli is a fantasy but its failing is that it is told in an amateur fashion. The film works as a visual extravaganza, but it fails to entertain.

name: Talvar
desc: Talvar gets your mind ticking along the murders' mysteries while it moves your heart at two lives - and one truth - lost.

name: Calendar Girls
desc: The story of the film resembles other Madhur Bhandarkar stories – a note from Page Three, a stroke of Fashion, far too much from Heroine.

name: Kis Kisko Pyaar Karoon
desc: When you watch a Kapil Sharma film with a straight face, you know there's something wrong. His character isn't funny enough as one would have expected.

name: Time Out
desc: Time Out may not have a hard-hitting story but it does make you think. Under its Richie Rich garb, lies a thought that’s enlightening and liberating.

name: Dunno Y 2 Life is a Moment
MSG 2- The Messenger
direc: Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh Ji Insan, Actor

name: Hero
desc: Hero offers bucketful of entertainment and victoriously conveys that commercial movies needn’t be puerile to show people a good time.

name: The Perfect Girl
desc: The film may not be ‘perfect’ per se but has its heart in the right place. The cinematography deserves a special mention as well.

name: Kaun Kitney Paani Mein
desc: Kaun Kitney Paani Mein touches upon a relevant issue but wraps it all too conveniently, without being confrontational.

name: Baankey Ki Crazy Baraat
desc: Baankey Ki Crazy Baraat is a formulaic family comedy, which you may not mind watching, if novelty is not what you seek.

name: Phantom
desc: If you’re still licking the wounds of that senseless Mumbai massacre, then Phantom is the balm you should reach out for.

name: All Is Well
desc: All Is Well lacks the cutting-edge sharpness or glittering depth of Umesh Shukla’s OMG. With its old-world feel, it’s not a cool cocktail but a teashop bun, dunked in sentimental tea.

name: Manjhi The Mountain Man
desc: Why this film that had so much potential doesn’t deserve superlatives is because of the inconsistency in the story-telling.

name: Gour Hari Dastaan: The Freedom File
desc: While the film does struggle with a slow pace and certain irrelevant characters and scenes that digress from the core subject, this biopic deserves to be seen.

name: Jaanisaar
desc: It’s a case of cinematic self-indulgence that doesn’t deserve to be compared to Ali’s masterpiece Umrao Jaan (1981). Poetic injustice!

name: Masaan
desc: The performances of the entire cast including that of the child actor Nikhil Sahni are praiseworthy. Masaan has pure desi magic woven in.

name: Bajrangi Bhaijaan
desc: Bajrangi Bhaijaan is Salman Khan's most daring film where Salman presents a beautiful performance - but allows the story to be the real dabangg.

name: I love NY
desc: It's a pity that certain multiplexes cancelled shows of this film, owing to low occupancy for its actually a decent romcom that you won't mind watching once.

name: Baahubali: The Beginning
desc: Touted as one of the most expensive films to be made in India, this highly anticipated part one of the two-part period epic, manages to enthrall you with its sheer scale and grandeur.

name: Guddu Rangeela
desc: The film works, albeit on some level, because of its gritty writing. What could have genuinely raised the bar though, is a slicker pace, additional gloss and superstar charisma.

name: Bezubaan Ishq
desc: Bezubaan Ishq looks like an unintentional spoof of dated romantic films. The animation used in the last scene will crack you up!

name: Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho
desc: Sadly, this social satire, which could have been an eye-opener on false cases and fraud witnesses, literally has more shit (pun intended) than substance.

name: Uvaa
desc: Uvaa manages to make sense somewhere, but shoddy execution mars this potentially significant social drama, which demands crucial changes in our judiciary and society at large.

name: Me
desc: ME is a movie that probably started out as a decent idea on paper, but fell completely flat on its face in execution, in almost every possible way.

name: P Se PM Tak
desc: Watching P Se PM Tak is like inviting depression. Bharat Jadhav should stick to Marathi plays, something he is good at.

name: Kuch Kuch Locha Hai
desc: KKLH is so tedious, inconsequential and long that by the end of it, you feel like you’ve spent days and not hours watching it.

name: Gabbar Is Back
desc: While the music's pleasantly seamless, the editing is razor-sharp, evoking Manmohan Desai, rushing you from one entertaining scene to the next, without time to figure things out.

name: Sabki Bajegi Band
desc: The film addresses topics like virginity, open relationships, extra-marital affairs, casting couch, and one night stands in probably the most immature way ever.

name: Ishq Ke Parindey
desc: This one has a Qayamat Se Qayamat Tak hangover. If you don’t mind traditional love stories and do not find them outdated, you can watch one.

name: Jai Ho Democracy
desc: With a talented cast at its disposal and even a decent plot, it’s a shame that the film fails to capitalise on either.

name: Mr. X
desc: Despite flaws, in its 133 minutes of runtime, Bhatt churns out a quasi-gratifying film, which has all the necessary commercial ingredients – from romance to good music to thunderous action sequences.

name: Nanak Shah Fakir
desc: While the film emerges as a clear winner in most departments, the length and shoddy makeup cannot be excused. The story is stretched way too much.

name: Margarita with a Straw
desc: It is deeply moving, a philosophical film which makes you wonder if the body is a palace or prison - and evokes mothers to lovers who've cherished your soul.

name: Barefoot to Goa
