desc: The film had the potential to be way more effective; nonetheless, it’s a sincere effort that deserves to be acknowledged.

name: Paisa Ho Paisa
desc: Low production value, poor dubbing, shoddy effects, atrocious songs, inconsequential concept and an irrelevant love story makes this journey a tiresome experience.

name: Detective Byomkesh Bakshy!
desc: A chilling climax masterfully ties up the tale - but 30 minutes less would've given this detective a much tighter grip. Still, DBB! is a fun watch.

name: Yahaan Sabki Lagi Hai
desc: Just when you think it might stand out for its unconventional approach and spontaneity, it goes into an arty zone that evolves into nothing.

name: Dozakh In Search of Heaven
desc: Zaigham Imam'€™s story is much stronger than his amateur execution. Nonetheless, it deserves to be seen for its sheer thought, which is brilliant.

name: Black Home
desc: If it's solely about spreading awareness, Black Home could be lauded for raising the issue that gets brushed under the carpet mostly. However, as a film, it fails to deliver on various grounds.

name: NH10
desc: It's easy to hate NH10 while watching it because it's one of the most terrifying Hindi films ever - while simultaneously, you love its brilliance.

name: Dirty Politics
desc: Silly isn't a term broad enough to encapsulate the zest of this movie. Stories like these demand a little more sensitivity.

name: Hey Bro
desc: It'€™s almost brutal to put one through the trauma of watching this film. At best, Hey Bro can be called a mind numbing experience.

name: Coffee Bloom
desc: If you find nothingness fascinating and are fine with films boasting of unhurried silences and stunning landscapes, you can give this indie film a shot.

name: Badmashiyaan
desc: Though it falls short of being an incredible movie but the unique style of narration, makes it pleasantly watchable.

name: Dum Laga Ke Haisha
desc: Dum Laga Ke Haisha is an unlikely quasi-original offering from the stable that in recent past has made sincere efforts to defy the conventional notions of love.

name: Ab Tak Chhappan 2
desc: Despite its flaws, ATC2 can be watched, if you are a diehard Nana Patekar fan. On second thoughts, watching the original again would be a smarter move.

name: Qissa
desc: Irrfan, Tisca and Tillotama give A-grade performances, making this film imminently watchable. If the filmmaker had decided to buck the pace up, the points being made here would have hit home harder.

name: Badlapur
desc: Brisk and absorbing, concluding differently than expected, Badlapur is an inspired film that dangerously attempts to change the landscape of the thriller genre in Bollywood.

name: Jai Jawaan Jai Kisaan
desc: For almost two hours, all you see is the protagonist suffering or making long speeches. Post interval, the film looks like a generic tale on India’s freedom fighters instead of Lal Bahadur Shastri.

name: Khamoshiyan
desc: If you find flying objects, animated butterflies, erotic dreams and the sight of letters being deleted automatically from a word document on a laptop scary, you deserve to watch Khamoshiyan alone.

name: Hawaizaada
desc: Hawaizaada works because this story about India’s unsung hero needs to find its place. But this realm depends heavily on performances – the histrionics could be several notches higher.

name: Rahasya
desc: As far as execution is concerned, while the unhurried unfolding of mystery adds depth to the film, it also demands patience from the viewers, which may or may not work in its favour.

name: Sharafat Gayi Tel Lene
desc: To sum it all up, the story had potential, but lacks chutzpah in its making. Too much of sharafat and no play make it a dull watch.

name: Alone
desc: The prolonged climax though it is full of twists, leaves you cold because it is too contrived. When you scratch the surface, you don't end up scared shitless.

name: Crazy Cukkad Family
desc: The characters are crazy enough to amuse you with their shenanigans. If you don’t mind a clichéd story, the film is worth a watch.

name: Tevar
desc: The director Amit Ravindernath Sharma makes a smooth progression from 30-second commercials to a 159-minute-long film.

name: Mumbai Can Dance Saalaa
desc: The film is so excruciatingly boring that it might change the opinion of those who were against the shutting down of dance bars.

name: PK
desc: PK is as much a philosophy as a film. It takes the 'stranded alien' theme, familiar from classics like ET, but tells the tale equally from the lonely alien's eyes.

name: Main Aur Mr. Riight
desc: Television actor Barun Sobti makes his Bollywood debut here and is probably the only saving grace of this film. Our hunt for the ‘perfect’ Bollywood rom-com continues.

name: Badlapur Boys
desc: While predictability of the plot can be forgiven since most sports-based films are about underdogs emerging victorious, the story must strike a chord with the audience, which doesn’t happen here.

name: Bhopal: A Prayer for Rain
desc: This grim tale that recounts the story of the biggest human tragedy caused because of the lethal methyl isocyanate (MIC) leak from the Union Carbide factory in Bhopal is compelling.

name: Action Jackson
desc: If you’re not looking for a mentally stimulating fare, enjoy this ride that is basically meant for the filmi keedas.

name: Ungli
desc: The film points a finger at our society, and rightly so. But much of the film is pointless too. This work of Rensil’s won’t leave a lasting fingerprint.

name: Zid
desc: The performances are forgettable and flaws scream out loud. The climax tries to shock, but leaves you shaken and wondering.

name: Zed Plus
desc: The subject matter could have been interesting but it is mired in tedious, very boring, rural and regional clichés that audiences have already seen, so many times.

name: Kill Dil
desc: What makes this film watchable is the effortless chemistry between Ranveer and Ali Zafar. Their poker-faced humour, jibes at one another and ability to break into a song are impressive.

name: Chaar Sahibzaade
desc: As an animation film, what it lacks is technology (given today’s 3D animation standards), Chaar Sahibzaade makes up for it with its strong and engaging content.

name: A Decent Arrangement
desc: A Decent Arrangement draws inspiration from Nagesh Kukunoor’s much acclaimed Hyderabad Blues but ends up being nothing more than a decent attempt at showing what has already been shown before.

name: Rang Rasiya
desc: Director Ketan Mehta merits applause for his portrait of painter Raja Ravi Varma, skillfully blending a biopic, a period film, a love story and a social critique, within a tight frame.

name: Fireflies
desc: In spite of the visual beauty of it all, what doesn’t go in the film’s favour is the story that drifts away and refuses to get back on track.

name: Happy New Year
desc: The cast pulls off their acts well; and leave you with some feel-good moments, but not enough to last three long hours.

name: Sonali Cable
desc: The film has a good concept but lacks the vibrancy and spirit of the city it is set in. Overall, it faces ‘connectivity’ issues.

name: Mumbai 125 Km 3D
desc: This film is somewhat like a Bollywoodised version of the Final Destination series. As horror, it partially works but as a slasher, gets too monotonous and repetitive...old wine in an old bottle.

name: Jigariyaa
desc: The film can be watched for its purity and simplicity. It ably captures the beauty of small towns and first love...love before technology happened. Love before sexual desire found its place in films.

name: Bang Bang
desc: Bang Bang makes more noise and little sense. This desi adaptation of Knight And Day, has charm in abundance, primarily because of its effervescent lead pair. But it lacks coherence.

name: 3 A.M
desc: 3 A.M is a conversation-heavy horror film. If that doesn’t put you off, you can give it a shot. Else, watch Insidious or The Conjuring once again on DVD.

name: Balwinder Singh Famous Ho Gaya
desc: While the first half decently entertains, things go haywire as the story progresses. Barring a scene or two, the writing is neither clever nor funny enough to make you laugh.

name: Desi Kattey
desc: Anand Kumar misses almost every target at making even a fairly watchable film. Damn the clichés, the film shows no semblance of a coherent story or believable characters.

name: Chaarfutiya Chhokare
desc: In spite of the presence of talented actors like Seema Biswas and Soha, uninspiring writing, poor editing and clichéd storytelling make the movie ineffective.

name: Meinu Ek Ladki Chaahiye
desc: A comic courtroom drama or a dramatic crime thriller…you keep wondering throughout, what is it that the filmmaker intended to make. Whatever the case, it fails to keep you awake, forget engaged.

name: Daawat-e-Ishq
desc: This one won’t fill your hungry hearts, but one serving (not too bland, not too spicy) isn’t too bad for your appetite.

name: Khoobsurat
desc: For the most part, the delightfully roguish romance between the lead couple tickles everything fun-loving inside you. That's what makes it so khoobsurat.

name: Khota Sikka
desc: No matter how inconsequential, the film may still find an audience in those who don't mind laughing at jokes, no matter how juvenile.

name: Creature 3D
desc: With the film being done in 3-D, you find the creature’s talons and tail reaching out for you in your auditorium seat. For a teeny-weeny part, that smile disappears.

name: Mary Kom
desc: The main reason why Mary Kom appeals is because it doesn't just give you a ringside view of boxing; it leaves you rooting for our sportsmen who have put India on the world map.

name: Katiyabaaz
desc: Sensitively directed, realistically shot, Katiyabaaz will make you value the most basic thing your city provides you with, that you often take for granted - bijli.

name: Mardaani
desc: While there is nothing in the plot that you haven't seen before, it is still watchable for the superb performance of Rani.

name: Life is Beautiful
desc: Those who are obsessed with love stories, no matter how inconsequential or conventional they are, won't mind watching this one.

name: Mad About Dance
desc: 'MAD' puts its best foot forward at the end, hold your breath for the last dance. Overall, it's a film for dance lovers. Even if it leaves the heart dancing for more.

name: Singham Returns
desc: It’s riddled with clichés and the length needs a good edit. But overall, it provides entertainment for enthusiasts of ‘Singham’ brand of cinema.

name: Entertainment
desc: Because the jokes are repetitive by nature, the LOL (laugh-out-loud) moments are few and far between. For the most part, the humour is for the child in you.

name: Lateef: The King of Crime
desc: You appreciate the makers for bringing this untold real-life story to celluloid. But at the end of the day, a biopic must affect you in some way, which doesn’t happen here.

name: Hate Story 2
desc: Even if the plot points in this vendetta drama seem asinine, with Surveen, Sunny and sex thrown in, the less pretentious will go home satiated.

name: Riyasat
desc: If you are planning to watch this film solely for Rajesh Khanna, don't. He looks unwell, can barely speak and thus seems to have been given very few dialogues.

name: Pizza
desc: The faint-hearted can stay away for the film does get immensely eerie. The rest should watch it for it’s one of the most unpredictable thrillers you will see in a long time.

name: Humpty Sharma Ki Dulhania
desc: HSKD has plenty of feel-good moments, but nothing that will leave you punch-drunk. For romantics who believe in their dils and their dulhanias.

name: Lekar Hum Deewana Dil
desc: Debutant director Arif Ali's Lekar Hum Deewana Dil is a sweet film that borrows the elopement theory from evergreen 70s'-80s' romances like Bobby, Love Story and Betaab.

name: Humshakals
desc: Shedding 30 minutes and some jaded gags would make Humshakals consistent fun - now, you laugh but also frequently go, ho-hum.

name: Machhli Jal Ki Rani Hai
desc: If you get spooked easily, you may not mind this one. If you like horror, watch Insidious (2010) or Ram Gopal Varma's Bhoot (2003) again. Those are classics.

name: F*ugly
desc: The result is like a soggy Delhi chaat where potentially spicy ingredients make a sorry mess. As F*ugly would phrase it, quite a f*waste.

name: Chal Bhaag
desc: While the motive and twists in the story are interesting, the comic execution ruins it. You don't see any humour in the situations or the characters.

name: Holiday – A Soldier Is Never Off Duty
desc: This one applauds the jawans who live in the jaws of death, and is a ‘wake up’ call for all the ‘sleepers’ that abound. Bravo!

name: Filmistaan
desc: In a nation of star-worshippers, this film devoid of superstars brilliantly stands out. Aaj khush toh bahut hain hum! Ab bas, tareef pe tareef...

name: Citylights
desc: The second half thus gently meanders, shots becoming slightly repetitive and slow, making you agree when Vishnu tells Deepak in exasperated humour, "Aap itni dheemi gati ke film hain!"

name: Kuku Mathur Ki Jhand Ho Gayi
desc: Funny situations and scenes with quirky characters provide clean humour but that can't substitute for the lack of a good, engaging story. Watch this one only if a 'little birdie' tells you to.

name: Heropanti
desc: Heropanti is enjoyable. The climax pumps up the action, featuring shirtless Tiger, crouching Rajjo. The tale has a twist as graceful as Tiger's flips.

name: Kochadaiiyaan
desc: Kochadiiyaan succeeds not because of technology but because of the writing. The story initially seems like a typical revenge fantasy but soon, we realize it is a bit more complex than that.

name: Children of War
desc: In spite of the odds, COH stands out for its earnest performances and thoughtful music. The film is tense and atmospheric. Wish it was more in-depth as well, given the gravity of the subject.

name: The X-pose
desc: This is far from a mind-bending thriller, but a decent effort which has some good 'ol masala to keep you entertained.

name: Koyelaanchal
desc: Koyelaanchal lacks a proper story. From coal mafia to collector’s baby to Karua’s change of heart to Maoist movements, you keep wondering what the film is all about!

name: Purani Jeans
desc: The concept of dosti symbolized as purani jeans is as old as cowboys in the wild west. But this denim offering leaves you ‘blue’ and ‘uncool’.

name: Kya Dilli Kya Lahore
desc: One of the finest things about ‘KDKL’ is Gulzar’s poetic prologue. Without the usual trappings of filmi fanfare, this story has its heart in the right place – pure and undivided.

name: Kaanchi
desc: Mr Ghai, you’re the maker of Kaalicharan, Vishwanath, Karz, Hero, Ram Lakhan, Karma, Pardes and Taal. Permit us to just rewind to your past glory.

name: Samrat & Co.
desc: While it’s brave of the conservative Rajshri productions to take the leap - from family dramas to thrillers, the effort should have been more compelling.

name: 2 States
desc: If you are in a mood for a Bollywood family saga with measured melodrama and the right amount of naach-gaana, visit 2 States.

name: Bhoothnath Returns
desc: Nitesh Tiwari’s sequel sets off with a lot of promise, entertainment, laughs and endearing camaraderie between a bhooth and a boy. The first-half has wittily written scenes.

name: Main Tera Hero
desc: Main Tera Hero is a pav bhaji picture, quick, spicy, hot. It has the depth of a comic strip but it also has its neon-shaded fun.

name: Dishkiyaoon
desc: For an action thriller, the narrative pace is so languid, you can take your popcorn and pee break between the times when two bullets are fired.

name: Station
desc: This concept could have worked better for a short film or a play. Nonetheless, watch it for the nonlinear narrative.

name: Ragini MMS 2
desc: For horror-buffs this might not be ‘spookilicious’ enough, but those looking for a ‘sun-sunny’ weekend, go lap it up!

name: Gang of Ghosts
desc: In the case of GOG, the only ones who seem to have had a blast are the actors - Mahie, Anupam, Saurabh and Jackie, all of who ham.

name: W
desc: The filmmaker chooses a sensitive, hard-hitting issue like rape, but barring the rape scenes and explicit dialogues, fails to get the gravity of the situation right.

name: Gulaab Gang
desc: Considering the subject's intense power and the charisma of these stars, the movie's hesitation with how to proceed stands out.

name: Queen
desc: This film belongs to its director Vikas Bahl. Earlier, he co-directed the National-Award winning 'Chillar Party' with Nitesh Tiwari. Bollywood should blow bugles in his honour.

name: Anuradha
desc: The film may have worked had it been a soap opera but otherwise, it’s painful to sit through this archaic tale of endless misery.

name: Shaadi Ke Side Effects
desc: The director strikes a fine balance between humour and emotion in this slice-of-marriage story. Single or married, this film will have more of a ‘special effect’ than ‘side effect’ on you.

name: Dee Saturday Night
desc: Prashant Narayanan does a decent job as a henchman of a Dubai-based don but his role is inconsequential and so is the film.

name: Darr @ The Mall
desc: The film might work for those who get frightened easily. For fans of the genre, watch Ragini MMS instead, if you still haven’t.

name: Ya Rab
desc: It may have started out as a noble intention, but the film’s execution is outdated and comes across as clichéd. The film might find appeal in mass audiences, which explains its style.

name: Heartless
desc: One doffs one’s hat to Shekhar for handling this difficult subject with such finesse. For someone so young and inexperienced, Adhyayan turns in a faultless performance.

name: Babloo Happy Hai
desc: Despite the shortcomings, the film manages to keep you engaged, thanks to the strong performances by the three lead actors and gorgeous cinematography.

name: One By Two
desc: The concept might look good on paper, but onscreen it dissipates like diarrhoea. Strung with a few laughable scenes, it scrambles around with too many plots crafted like episodic sitcoms.

name: Jai Ho
desc: The story is laced with light-hearted humour and massy music. Like most Salman Khan films, this one too rests solely on his undeniable superstardom.

name: Karle Pyaar Karle
desc: Dialogue like 'either you have *shit in your b*m or dum in your b*m*' make you cringe. The film is full of clichés of mainstream cinema.

name: Dedh Ishqiya
desc: Vishal Bharadwaj's dialogue keeps you in splits. The free usage of words like sex and ch***yapaa tickle the funny bone.

name: Mokssh
desc: Mokssh scores in almost all departments, story and authenticity, imagination, cinematography, dialogues and performances.

name: Mahabharat
desc: What makes this version thoroughly enjoyable is the talent that has lent its voice to each of the prominent characters.

name: What the Fish
desc: The ‘idea’ behind the movie can be appreciated for its novelty but it fails to develop into a full-fledged comedy of errors, which was the intention.

name: Lucky Kabootar
desc: If Lucky Kabootar was meant to be a romantic comedy, not a single scene makes you laugh or feel the love. The crudity of the language makes you cringe instead.

name: Club 60
desc: Club 60 is essentially a heart-rending tale of a couple, coping with an irreparable loss. In spite of flaws, you can watch it solely for the immensely talented Farooque Shaikh and the sublime Sarika.

name: Singh Saab The Great
desc: Anil Sharma's Singh Saab the Great has its heart in the correct place. Sunny Deol's earnestness shines, throughout the duration of this melodrama.

name: Satya 2
desc: The film reiterates, “Company ek ‘soch’ hai.” We wish RGV had put in some soch into this. Truth be told, iss film ko goli maaro, and for the sake of nostalgia, watch the original, for posterity.

name: Krrish 3
desc: For sheer vision, bravado and superlative execution, this one soars to new orbits. Latch on to this cape for an exhilarating ride.

name: Sooper Se Ooper
desc: Sooper se Ooper is unconventional and thus not clichéd. It’s a decent entertainer. Sadly, it’s not as funny as we had expected it to be either.

name: Baat Bann Gayi
desc: There is no comedy or entertainment either, and for a film that intends to be funny, this one ends up being tardy and way too predictable for your liking.

name: War Chhod Na Yaar
desc: Black comedy is a rare genre in Bollywood and hats off to director for bringing it to the forefront. His subject is relevant, given the many unpleasant cross-border incidents that have occurred.

name: Warning 3D
desc: ‘Warning’, heavily inspired from Hollywood film ‘Open Water 2’ with all its highs and lows is a new effort at a waterworld story, but fails to safely swim ashore even with a life-vest.

name: Super Model
desc: With trashy production values, a futile story, cheesy dialogues and catastrophic performances, this one trips off the ramp long before the show starts.

name: Maazii
desc: Maazii is a dark, haunting and unconventional tale of crime and redemption. In spite of no big names associated with it, it manages to hold your attention till the end.

name: Zanjeer
desc: This film should be judged as a stand-alone offering because attempts to compare the two versions will find the current one falling short, especially in the dialogue and music departments.

name: The Light: Swami Vivekananda
desc: This is one film you must avoid watching for neither does it inspire you, nor does it make you want to know more about him.

name: Madras Cafe
desc: Sircar never overindulges in gore, keeping Madras Café a shifting site of mental violence. The film deserves an extra half-star for guts, going for the gunpowder - but with a restrained hand.

name: Once Upon Ay Time In Mumbai Dobaara!
Chennai Express
desc: Shah Rukh’s attempts at comedy go from convincing to convoluted. But, for the most part, he lights up the screen with his effervescence.

name: Rabba Main Kya Karoon
desc: The film provides few laughs, but mostly lacks comedy or romance. It bursts into random songs and the climax leaves you laughing – for the wrong reasons.

name: Calapor
desc: The intent is good and we get the message, but shoddy execution fails to elicit a response or provoke sympathy for convicts who may want to change their lives for the better.

name: Bajatey Raho
desc: A film without star-power depends largely on convincing performances. Dolly Ahluwalia, on a roll since Vicky Donor, is adept as are Ravi Kishan, Tusshar, Ranveer and Vinay.

name: Luv U Soniyo
desc: The film sends out a good message to youngsters like 'family comes first', 'respect your elders', etc. It has its share of sweet moments, but overall, as a rom-com, it fails to leave a mark.

name: Nasha
desc: Amit Saxena's erotic thriller shows more emotion than eroticism. It has some flashes and moods of his first outing 'Jism', though at a story level it falls way behind.

name: Tara-- The Journey of Love & Passion
desc: Films are conceived with an idea. In this case, it should probably have been left as one because its execution leaves much to be desired.

name: Bhaag Milkha Bhaag
desc: Mehra infuses realism into drama, and explores characters so deeply and sensitively through tragedy and triumph, that it sparks an emotional deluge.

name: Policegiri
desc: If films like Wanted, Dabangg and Singham entertain you and if you like Sanju baba's style, Policegiri is bound to make you whistle.

name: Lootera
desc: In his second outing, post-the critically acclaimed Udaan (2010), director Vikramaditya Motwane definitely shows an upward graph.

name: Ghanchakkar
desc: The director, is 'inspired’ by innumerable Hollywood and UK black humour flicks. The film has an interesting premise.

name: Ankur Arora Murder Case
desc: While the film is an eye-opener on medical skullduggery, it fails to become cutting edge cinema because the screenplay offers few surprises.

name: Mere Haule Dost
desc: The film is as purposeless as the characters in it. The title track of the film is probably the only good thing about this amateurish film.

name: Ishkq In Paris
desc: Preity Zinta’s maiden production has its aesthetics in place. Paris is enchanting. The actress is good but there ends the show.

name: I Don't Luv U
desc: The film has a lot to offer, especially for youngsters but mentions of too many moralistic issues leave you frustrated. The film tries too hard to cater to the young generation and their dilemmas.

name: Beehad -The Ravines
desc: The idea and intention behind this film was probably sound, but the execution falls far short of what this movie could actually have turned out to be.

name: Gippi
desc: Sonam Nair's ‘coming of puberty’ film handles simple issues sensitively, though it doesn’t delve too deep. The subtlety appeals, but lacks drama in the second half, with a mediocre climax.

name: Chhota Bheem and the Throne of Bali
Celluloid Man
desc: Films mean much more to Nair than entertainment. "I understand the world and people better through cinema" says he. If you feel the same, don't miss out on this one.

name: Shootout At Wadala
desc: The film ultimately belongs to Gupta, who stays true to the genre and makes a welcome return to the credible lot of Bollywood directors.

name: Life Mein Hungama Hai
desc: Direction is decent but it's the performances and the story that keeps you hooked. Overall, it's a decent vacation film for the children, made with a modest budget.

name: Ek Thi Daayan
desc: Kannan Iyer makes an impressive debut…and kudos to Ekta Kapoor and Vishal Bharadwaj for allowing him to bring his daayan to life without compromises.

name: Nautanki Saala!
desc: This is no Shakespearean act, but there’s enough drama, demons and devtaas to rival our desi phantoms of the operas.

name: Commando - A One Man Army
desc: If you are an action junkie and if you have peaked on Sylvester Stallone’s Rambo-series, then our desi Commando, is what you will term paisa-vasool entertainment.

name: Chashme Baddoor
desc: This version's as different as paapri chaat from a dhokla. But it retains the original's madness, masti and movie-mania.

name: Himmatwala
desc: This one might impress the wannabe Himmatwalas out there. But it’ll take more than himmat to go back to the gawdiest era of all.

name: Mere Dad Ki Maruti
desc: Don't expect an out-and-out comedy, the film is a light-hearted family entertainer with a message for the youth. Do take your dad along for it, in his gaddi!

name: I, Me Aur Main
desc: This niche movie doesn't nail it but it's a cute watch, floating by humming - "Take it easy, thora moody, thora cheesy."

name: Jayantabhai Ki Luv Story
desc: The screenplay is average and it waits a while to take-off. And we wish it had a bit more ‘Ram Leela’ but overall it entertains.

name: The Unsound
desc: Don’t know about the hero but at least you wouldn't hurt your brain, if you skip ‘The Unsound’ and let it remain ‘unseen’ or ‘unheard’ of!

name: Deewana Main Deewana
desc: You go to the theatre, preparing yourself to sit through an 'old' film and thus, in spite of it being decently entertaining, it fails to grip your attention.

name: Main Krishna Hoon
desc: It is the presence of Lord Krishna that will make the kids in particular, ignore the flaws and enjoy the film which has both mischief and tears.

name: Akaash Vani
desc: Akaash Vani makes women realize that it’s more important to be happy and respected than being considered as righteous. It works strongly as social drama than a love story.

name: Bandook
desc: Bandook leaves you a tad confused about what exactly the filmmaker intends to portray. Positively, it doesn't glorify gun violence and captures the UP mafia well.

name: Mumbai Mirror
desc: It has flaws in the first half, and also too many killings - random and ruthless. However, the second half sums up the suspense – blood soaked in tragic truths and raw realities.

name: Matru Ki Bijlee Ka Mandola
desc: With its intellectual foundation and dramatic potential, MKBKM needed disciplined direction, not wandering shots, predictable banter or dull crudity.

name: Meri Shadi Karao
desc: While the film isn't revolting or something equally bad, there's nothing much for you to get entertained by either. The film could have probably been better, had it been in Punjabi.

name: Rajdhani Express
desc: The film does speed up and changes track for the better towards the end, but the thrill comes too late. That pace was needed throughout the film.

name: The Last Act
desc: With a unique concept at hand and an all-new directors’ gang, getting the ‘act together’ is no mean feat. Team of 12 – Take a bow, this stage is all yours.

name: Khiladi 786
desc: For those looking for some logic-less laughtime, groovy tunes topped with some todh-podh – this one could bring some action to your weekend.

name: Jab Tak Hai Jaan
desc: Jab Tak Hai Jaan is the swan song of Yash Chopra, the big daddy of romance. Every frame is picture perfect, the emotions are well nuanced.

name: Keymon & Nani In Space Adventure
desc: Barring few insignificant dull moments, lead character Keymon is indeed a ‘dude’. Take your kids to watch him mimic Shah Rukh Khan, Saif and Shakti Kapoor!

name: Future Toh Bright Hai Ji
desc: The film would have worked better as a sentimental drama. Were it not for the forced humour, the film wouldn't be as forgettable.

name: Sons Of Ram – Heroes Will Rise
desc: Director Kaushal Ruia doesn’t showcase masterpiece in terms of visual brilliance and special effects, but he can take a bow for his storytelling which wins you over.

name: Ata Pata Laapata
desc: The preachiness and repetition bores you to death. Guess the intention was to make a musical satire. Songs seem like fillers, which only add to the length of the movie, but nothing to the story.

name: Rush
desc: While not the relentless thriller it could've been, Rush offers some slick seconds. But despite all that, Rush lacks zip.

name: Ajab Gazabb Love
desc: This film is all about a bunch of people going bananas, yet, it doesn’t leave you in splits. But if you care for a few giggles, go watch it.

name: Chakravyuh
desc: Chakravyuh is a hard film to make and marks must be given to Jha for sticking his neck out. Staying true to the subject, he gives us an insight into uncomfortable truths.

name: Shudra: The Rising
desc: Shudra attempts to overthrow the age-old caste system in India. Watch it, if you are still not enlightened enough on the issue.

name: Prem Mayee
desc: Prem Mayee is about a girl who feels lost and depressed, unfortunately, that is exactly what you feel after watching this potentially meaningful but meaningless film!

name: Makkhi
desc: Though the plot is for the most-part predictable, Makkhi still offers situations that are truly gleeful to the young and the old alike.

name: Chittagong
desc: Like a Chittagong orchid, the movie takes time to blossom - but when it does, it's beautiful. And pleases a certain master.

name: Login
desc: Film is high on drama but also has just the right amount of comedy and suspense that keeps you hooked. On the flip side, editing, dubbing lacks finesse. It could have been better.

name: In The Name Of Tai
desc: Nishigandha Wad is the reason you hope the film will take off somewhere, and it does in the second half to a small extent.

name: Pairon Talle
desc: There are moments where you empathize with the characters, and you're waiting for the film's idea to germinate, but it gets 'trampled' along the way. This one isn't a 'class' apart.

name: English Vinglish
desc: Easily one of the best films of 2012; it is tale of women empowerment because it strikes a chord, right from the start to the end titles.

name: Heroine
desc: The saving grace of the film is Kareena, who not only looks drop-dead gorgeous but is also adept as the girl interrupted.

name: Jeena Hai Toh Thok Daal
desc: Straight up - Jeena Hai Toh Thok Daal (JHTTD) is a nightmare. My strongest objection to it is its extreme violence in language.

name: Riwayat
desc: Dramatic music would’ve helped but it’s missing. So is acting with depth and taut direction. All of which is a pity.

name: From Sydney With Love
desc: The low-on-EQ (Emotional Quotient) stuff takes away all the charm from this movie which has an otherwise fresh star cast.

name: Joker
desc: It's a totally off-the-wall entertainer powered by corny jokes, OTT filmy characters and tongue-in-cheek sequences. If you like that stuff, you'll laugh out loud. If you don't, it's not for you.

name: Shirin Farhad Ki Toh Nikal Padi
Overtime
desc: Forget better late than never. Sometimes it’s better never than late. That’s precisely the case with this Bollywood film which should have never made it to the screens.

name: Krishna Aur Kans
desc: Kudos to the filmmakers for bringing to life the very tale of we have all grown up on and hope the Generation-to-be will grow up on.

name: Jism-2
desc: 'Jism 2' has many surprises but without some plot absurdities, the film could have been tighter. Slicker. And hotter.

name: Aalaap
desc: Right up, Aalaap is unabashedly a movie by debutantes – its director, cast and crew are largely first-timers. This has pluses and minuses.

name: Challo Driver
desc: This concept could be wittily humorous, but it’s punctured by uninspiring dialogues, zombie-like expressions and speedbreaker-scenes.

name: Mere Dost Picture Abhi Baki Hai
desc: Director Rajnish Raj Thakur, attempts a behind-the-scenes dekho of Bollywood - an expose, a tongue-in-cheek reality check of sorts, but eventually rolls out a mash-up of an incomplete showreel.

name: Gattu
desc: Gattu is a must-watch for children of all ages (read: grown-ups even more). And if you think you’re too grown up for a kiddie film, go fly a kite.

name: Cocktail
desc: What Cocktail should be truly applauded for is its permissiveness. As a film it breaks, shackles and ushers in a new free spirit that Gen-Now will relate to.

name: 3 Bachelors
desc: There are a couple of one liners (out-and-out adult, mind you) and moments that manage to make you laugh, somewhat. But then it’s all in flashes, primarily in the first half.

name: Bol Bachchan
desc: The movie has a constant up-and-down aspect to it, one sequence making you shriek in your seat with laughter, another sending your mind wandering off to the mundane.

name: Daal Mein Kuch Kaala Hain
desc: A suitcase full of cash is the shortcut to success for this wannabe actor. So much so, she is ready to say ‘yes’ to a crazy, not-her-type movie maker.

name: Maximum
desc: There are scenes where the director triggers good performances, but with the inclusion of too many facts, figures and case files, the film loses entertainment value.

name: Teri Meri Kahaani
desc: Even with a powerhouse of talent; the script lacks depth and fails to ignite enough passion or chemistry for a love story.

name: Chakradhaar
desc: Sadly, more than finding solutions to the varied education problems, the movie ends up as an action packed war between the bad guy and our very own super hero.

name: Shanghai
desc: Director Dibakar Banerjee’s adaptation of Greek writer Vassilis Vassilikos’s book 'Z' is impressively Indianized. The story-telling is embossed with naked realism, rawness and brutal honesty.

name: Rowdy Rathore
desc: The film's an unabashed, gunpowder-hot, sambar-spiced star-vehicle which runs along energetically most of the time because its star - Akshay Kumar.

name: Rakhtbeej
desc: Rakhtbeej is a film you laugh at, not with, the kinda movie you could see with pals, popcorn and a cushion to pop behind when someone’s ear gets slashed or arms crushed. The film’s full of howlers.

name: Yeh Khula Aasmaan
desc: For a movie that’s supposed to be inspirational, director (Gitanjali Sinha) gives us blah lines, lackluster story-telling - which is emotional at times, with an exhaustingly slow pace.

name: Love Recipe
desc: The film is filled with lots of chaos, non-humorous one liners and loads of songs. If only the recipe of real love was that easy.

name: Love, Wrinkle-Free
desc: It’s simple, pure, and breaks cosmetic clichés - that’s the beauty. But halfway through the film, the wrinkles steep deeper, in the script that is.

name: Arjun: The Warrior Prince
desc: This journey of a superhero is more for adults than kids on their summer holiday. Of all the amateurish animation films we’ve seen, this one’s a ‘God-sent’.

name: Chhota Bheem And The Curse Of Damyaan
desc: You might choose to overlook the loopholes considering there is hardly happening entertainment for kids in desi cinema.

name: The Forest
desc: The Forest features excellent sound design, silences resounding with unknown dangers, music silken but unobtrusive. The film is a warning that should be watched.

name: Dangerous Ishhq
desc: In a frantic effort to immortalize Karisma’s comeback, director Vikram Bhatt has gone too far back in time. And left us weary with all the time travel.

name: Tezz
desc: Despite slick action and stunning scenes – bullets ramming underwater into a sunlit stream, a violet flower-bush before a cop-car – Tezz loses speed often.

name: Life Ki Toh Lag Gayi
desc: Watch it at your own risk, but remember, we warned you. Given a choice, we’d like the real city and a drive on Mumbai’s roads - it probably has fewer potholes than this story.

name: Chhodo Kal Ki Baatein
desc: This dramedy has a couple of songs, an item number (Rum Mein Gham) and fine actors, but all this fails to amplify the seed of thought.

name: Housefull 2
desc: Housefull-2 is a bag of laughs with eye-candy - Akshay in linens, Jacqueline in minis - and some crackling performances.

name: Agent Vinod
desc: Agent Vinod is slick and visually stylized, but loses steam at times. The movie is a tad long and often creatively compromised.

name: Say Yes To Love
desc: Maybe 80s action is back (Dabangg, Singham); but this romance from 20 years ago knocks us out more than Salman and Ajay ever could!

name: Chaurahen-Crossroads
desc: There are some scenes that are well executed but it ends on a predictable note that doesn’t move you to tears, or fuel an intellectual overdrive.

name: Diary of a Butterfly
desc: Diary of a Butterfly seems to be a vehicle of sorts for Udita Goswami. She probably gets more screen time than rest of the cast put together. But this is the sort of vehicle that goes nowhere.

name: ?: A question mark
desc: Go and drench yourself in fear. Couples watching the film might find themselves clinging to one another for reasons other than love.

name: Married 2 America
desc: The film is generously littered with cuss words and a titillating scene where a female cop feels up the leading lady. Single-screen theatres might yet find some viewers.

name: Valentine's Night
desc: Valentine’s Night ends up like one of those car drivers in the movie who don't know where to go and keep circling the streets of Delhi.

name: Staying Alive
desc: There are few major dramatic moments in the film. It isn’t easy holding the audience interest through a series of conversations inside an ICU. But director Mahadevan manages to do that.

name: Agneepath
desc: There's both style and craft in the way director builds the film's opening and closing scenes. You feel you are in the middle of a real execution.

name: Pappu Can't Dance Saala
desc: It's a refreshing film which keeps you involved with its sensitive portrayal of two lonely souls trying to find succour in an alien city. Watch it. You won't get bored.

name: Lanka
desc: It is the length of the film and its somewhat laboured tenor which works against it. A bit of pruning and editing would have worked favourably for it.

name: Ek Main Ek Tum
desc: There's too little horror to keep the goosebumps coming. Too many songs and dances divert the plot and a sub-plot about an alternate romance is truly irksome.

name: I Am Singh
desc: Meant as a ready reckoner on Sikhism, the film should have had a larger appeal. Unfortunately it will find its target audience, mostly in its own community.

name: The Dirty Picture
desc: The Dirty Picture is definitely not only your film for the week, but is a seminal work that will be studied in feminist discourses.

name: Shakal Pe Mat Ja
desc: A bit more training and gravitas in their approach towards the craft, then maybe there could be a film to watch out from this young group of wannabe filmmakers.

name: Damadamm!
desc: Ironically, it's the songs of the film which stand out much more than the script, narrative, drama and performances.

name: Jumbo 2: The Return Of The Big Elephant
Be Careful
desc: More than half of the movie goes into getting cheap thrills out of a possible rape encounter to please the girl everybody wants to bed. Avoid.

name: Mod
desc: It's the pace of the film that takes its toll on you. The events unfold with extenuating lethargy and test your patience time and again.

name: Jo Dooba So Paar -- It's love in Bihar!
desc: The film holds up a charming mirror on the small town milieu and creates heroes out of ordinary folks. Surely, a different experience.

name: Aazaan
desc: Don't go looking for something really deep and incisive in this popcorn thriller which has nothing to boast about except its exotic locales.

name: Love Breakups Zindagi
desc: Not quite the perfect debut from Sahil Sangha as director and Dia and Zayed as producers, Love Breakups Zindagi should be treated as a stepping stone to something more substantial from the threesome.

name: Chargesheet
desc: Other than Dev Anand, the rest of the actors are quite irrelevant, including the random girls and boys who keep flitting across the screen. Dev saab takes care of all the drama.

name: Saheb Biwi Aur Gangster
desc: The film may be a finely crafted drama, yet it unfolds with thriller pace, keeping you on the edge of the seat till the very end.

name: Hum Tum Shabana
desc: Hum Tum Shabana is meant to make you laugh. But the entire first half slips through without eliciting a single smile. The end result is that it is just time-pass.

name: Mausam
desc: Mausam has lots to offer to the viewer who doesn't mind his cinema languorous, laid back and moody, with loads of beauty.

name: Speedy Singhs
desc: A little more spice and edge to the delineation of the game itself would have made the film an action-packed adventure too. Nevertheless, Speedy Singhs is an entertaining watch.

name: Mummy Punjabi
desc: The problem with Mummy Punjabi lies in the fact that it is neither a comedy nor a serious film, just something in-between. Wonder who is the target audience!

name: Bodyguard
desc: The film sparks up only in the action sequences which showcase Salman as the essential action hero who can perform the most impossible stunts.

name: Shabri
desc: The action is fast-paced, the acting is immensely watchable and Shabri ends up as a stylish debut by director Lalit Marathe.

name: Not a Love Story
desc: Gory, yes but Not A Love Story is an interesting study of the darker and more devious spots of friendly neighbourhood types.

name: Chatur Singh Two Star
desc: The filmmaker fails to use any of his comic actors, and he has so many of them. Consummate comic actors like Satish Kaushik, Sanjay Mishra and Suresh Menon completely fail to cheer you.

name: Aarakshan
desc: Aarakshan was rocking till the first half. But as an omnibus on the travails of India's education system, it flounders into no-man's land.

name: I Am Kalam
desc: It's inspirational, intelligent, topical and entertaining too. More importantly, it brims over with heart and soul, leaving no one untouched with its simple message.

name: Chala Mussadi Office Office
desc: In the celluloid version, Pankaj Kapoor once again proves what a fine actor he is as he carries forth the relentless struggle of the aam Indian against India's endemic bribe culture.

name: Gandhi to Hitler
desc: The only person who seems to get a slight hold on her character is Neha Dhupia who doesn’t reduce Eva Braun to a parody unlike the other historical figures.

name: Khap
desc: A bit of subtlety and a more artistic vision would have gone a long way in creating a strong social document on screen.

name: Bubble Gum
desc: Bubble Gum may not score high on the entertainment quotient and is definitely not meant for the popcorn guzzlers. But the film has a piquant charm to it.

name: Singham
desc: Rohit Shetty's retro film leaves you goofy, grinning and clapping with glee as the rivals indulge in in-your-face encounters.

name: Delhi Belly
desc: Delhi Belly is a fine example of how the brightest and the boldest, when they pool in their talent, can create a film that is guaranteed to give you your money's worth.

name: Double Dhamaal
desc: This one's definitely not for the fastidious, choosy viewer but for those who don't mind losing it for a bit, Double Dhamaal works like an average Bollywood comedy.

name: Always Kabhi Kabhi
desc: It's all foregone and predictable apart from being inordinately long. School is agony; school is ecstasy. Always Kabhi Kabhi captures neither and treads the staid middle ground.

name: Bhindi Baazaar Inc.
desc: The film takes too long to get on course and is cluttered with loose, untidy bits that need to be edited out. What works in favour is the authenticity of the setting and the changing tide of events.

name: Bheja Fry 2
desc: The humour is laid back, the laughs are too few and far between and the tango between Vinay Pathak and Kay Kay Menon lacks the chemistry.

name: Love Express
desc: The film unfolds inside a train, with each compartment throwing up a different story, featuring an odd assortment of people. Kind of gets you travel weary. Most of the stories have no substance.

name: A Strange Love Story
desc: It's an old-fashioned tale about spooks and spirits that takes so long to unfold, you lose patience, attention, interest.
The highpoint of the film lies in the fact that it explores paranormal activity without abandoning science and rationality. And that indeed is a rare achievement.

name: Shagird
desc: Punctuated with thrilling chases and shoot-outs in the crowded by-lanes of Delhi, Shagird is another interesting film from maverick director Tigmanshu Dhulia.

name: Love U... Mr Kalakaar!
desc: The film does have a sweetness that grows on you and seasoned actors like Ram Kapoor and Madhoo add a dignity to their roles, but the film is so predictable and so long, it loses impact.

name: Luv Ka The End
desc: Great idea, poor execution: that's the irony of this film which promises to catapult Yash Raj Films as the MTV of the film industry.

name: Shor In The City
desc: This one's a completely quirky cameo on Mumbai - a city that continues to hypnotize people with its chameleon hues. Don't miss this black comedy that has heart and soul.

name: Dum Maaro Dum
desc: There is the stylization of the film and its dramatic narration that makes it a compelling watch. This one's complete paisa vasool fare.

name: Teen Thay Bhai
desc: The film ends up as a half-blown venture where there are too many theatrics and too many loosely edited scenes to allow the film to unfold as an uninterrupted laugh riot.

name: F.A.L.T.U
desc: The problem with F.A.L.T.U lies in its tone. It doesn't know whether to unfold as a full blown comedy or take itself seriously.

name: Shinchan: Bungle in the Jungle
desc: The young audience gets restless and fidgety, waiting for the fun to begin. Enid Blyton's Famous Five would definitely be a better bet than the Shinchan defence army of five.

name: Monica
desc: Don't be mislead by the title (no, it isn't a morning show film) and don't be foxed by the low key publicity. This one's truly a surprise. Check it out.

name: Satrangee Parachute
desc: The storyline may be interesting and hold potential as a drama about a bunch of kids trying to blow up a terrorist plot. But its delineation is so serious and so unfunny, it makes us adults fidgety.

name: 7 Khoon Maaf
desc: Serious, sensitive and stirring, 7 Khoon Maaf is a whole new cinematic experience. Watch how Indian cinema is metamorphosing into something more substantial and global.

name: Patiala House
desc: Watch this family drama for its redefinition of patriotism in a going-global age, dominated by the growing Indian diaspora.

name: Utt Pataang
desc: Intermittently interesting, Utt Pataang has a problem of plenty. You've seen this so many times in experimental gangster noir.

name: Yamla Pagla Deewana
desc: Watch it for its unbridled goofiness, the attempt to laugh at the Punjabi stereotypes and for the Deol chemistry that makes you chuckle.

name: Turning 30
desc: Refreshing, unusual and unlike your typical women-oriented films, Turning 30 marks an addition to the increasing tribe of intelligent women directors.

name: Vikalp
desc: The drama lacks punch and gets too long drawn in places. The romance and the song and dance frills were unnecessary. A bit of chopping, sifting and editing would have worked wonders for the film.

name: Ada: A Way Of Life
desc: Sadly, the message and the meaning gets lost in translation. What remains is the stylisation of the film and the music.

name: Toonpur Ka Superhero
desc: Toonpur Ka Superrhero is great goodwill-hunting Christmas fare. Enjoy the upmarket animation and Bollywood's adventurism into brand new territory.

name: Isi Life Mein
desc: The film unfolds as one long play rehearsal and doesn't seem to move forward after a point. Wish there had been some spirit too in this well-intentioned film.

name: 332 Mumbai To India
desc: The film is a flat narration of an event with no attempt at character building and dramatic rendering. The hurried connection of the anti-migrants agitation with 26/11 makes no sense at all.

name: Kaalo
desc: The film has some stylish cinematography and captures the eerie desert land picturesquely. But the horror exists only as long as Kaalo stays out of the frame as an ominous presence in the backdrop.

name: Payback
desc: Watch out for a winning performance by Zakir Hussain and Mukesh Rishi in this simple uncluttered film which has a different appeal.

name: Mirch
desc: The garbled end and the misconstrued tenor of the film acts as a deterrent. But Raima and Konkona are a treat to watch.

name: No Problem
desc: No Problem will make you forget your problems, provided you are willing to get goofy and give up your quest for meaning in masala.

name: Rakta Charitra 2
desc: Rakht Charitra doesn't break new ground like Satya and Company, nevertheless it remains a must-see film for Ramu fans.

name: Khelein Hum Jee Jaan Sey
desc: Khelein Hum Jee Jaan Sey helps you rediscover forgotten heroes -- and a forgotten sentiment -- at a time when a scam-tainted nation needs to celebrate the national sentiment the most.

name: Allah Ke Bandey
desc: Allah Ke Bandey isn't meant to entertain you. It is a film that makes you sit up and send out a silent lament for the loss of innocence.

name: Shahrukh Bola Khoobsurat Hai Tu
desc: The film does have a few rough edges and needs a bit of editing. But it exudes a sense of novelty that keeps the moments ticking.

name: Guzaarish
desc: A film like Guzaarish isn't made for the box office. It's made for the gratification of the senses. And that it does, in ample measure.

name: A Flat
desc: The entire second half of the film focuses on the non-happening exploits of a non-acting lass who poses as an unspoilt mountain girl with a spoilsport boyfriend. Give us some real goosebumps please!

name: Dunno Y Na Jaane Kyun
desc: There is a degree of sensitivity while tackling the homosexual relationship, nevertheless the drama lacks punch and the conclusion becomes self-defeatist.

name: Maalik Ek
desc: There is a warmth and simplicity in the narration, although the over abundance of songs and commentary does act as a deterrent. This one's a biography that's essentially meant for the believers.

name: Nakshatra
desc: The film is in desperate need of editing and punch. Anupam Kher's two-bit role in the film doesn't justify his presence.

name: Daayen Ya Baayen
desc: Daayen ya Baayen works because of the authenticity of its backdrop and the realistic performances by the motley cast.

name: Hisss
desc: The carnage that the serpent unleashes is grotesque and her transformation from seductress woman to venomous reptile is more funny than eyeball-grabbing.

name: Rakta Charitra
desc: What makes the film watchable are a few set pieces which bear the masterly imprint of the film maker who redefined the action genre in Indian cinema.

name: Jhootha Hi Sahi
desc: The script has a few teasing twists and turns that do not let the film fall into the rut of predictable run-of-the-mill romances.

name: Ramayana: The Epic
desc: Shred of all sermons, Ketan Mehta's (producer) Ramayana works like magical pop art: An Andy Warhol version of an eternal Indian superhero.

name: Knock Out
desc: Director Mani Shankar scripts a thriller, which holds your attention and manages to make an important point: Weed out corruption and see where India soars.

name: Lava Kusa
desc: The film is too long. The language is too archaic. The animation is too flat. The narrative has too many songs. The action sequences lack testosterone.

name: Do Dooni Chaar
desc: Do Dooni Chaar is a be-fitting ode to the teaching community and makes you remember all those wonderful teachers who taught you some of the most important lessons of life.

name: For Real
desc: It is a film that scores well on the freshness and reality quotient. Watch it for the new approach towards a familiar subject.

name: Dabangg
desc: For those who celebrate and serenade the 'silliness' of mainstream masala movie lore and swear by its popcorn quotient, Dabangg is the greatest getaway of the season.

name: Mallika
desc: The film doesn't move at all and comes undone because of the most garbled screenplay till date and you have a movie that ain't even time pass.

name: We Are Family
desc: You end up squeezing a lot of wet tissues especially in the second half -- by the time the movie ends and walk out with a leaden heart.

name: The Film Emotional Atyachar
desc: Quirky as it comes, but not enough of crookedness to pitch it in the league of Johnny Gaddar and the likes, Emotional Atyachar is a black comedy that mostly ends up grey.

name: Antardwand
desc: Get real. Go for Antardwand. The film boasts of some fine performances and has deservedly been applauded with the National Award for Best Film on social issues.

name: Soch Lo
desc: Soch Lo is indeed the surprise package of the week, offering a new cinematic experience to the viewer who likes his cinema packaged differently: a bit over the top, unpredictable, absolutely edgy.

name: Hello Darling
desc: Please stay away from this film which reduces a serious issue like sexual harassment at the workplace to a total farce.

name: Help
desc: The horror angle works intermittently when you sit up and take note of the paranormal proceedings. For the rest of the film, you are mostly counting the minutes.

name: Peepli Live
desc: Peepli Live is a lively and living document on the 'other' India, that lives beyond the neon lights and the cruising metros. Another ace up Aamir Khan's sleeve.

name: Aisha
desc: This must be one of the most exquisitely crafted films to sashay down Bollywood's boulevard in the non-action genre.

name: Once Upon A Time In Mumbaai
Udaan
desc: Udaan is unconventional Bollywood at its biting best. The film is a moody, introspective and ekdum different look at teenage angst.

name: Milenge Milenge
desc: Milenge Milenge ends up as a might-have-been, iffy affair. Watch it 'IF' you still dig the Shahid-Kareena jodi which re-defined the word 'chemistry' in Jab We Met.

name: Red Alert: The War Within
desc: Red Alert does make you sit up and demand attention especially in a season when political cinema is raising its banner in Bollywood.

name: Mr Singh Mrs Mehta
desc: The film is a refreshing walk off the beaten Bollywood track and scores on its minimalist approach to matrimonial discord.

name: Krantiveer-The Revolution
desc: It's a brave effort to create a lost world, but alas! Bollywood has marched miles ahead from the days of yore and yelldom.

name: Raavan
desc: The film is literally a work of art where one luminescent frame follows another as the scenes keep shifting from one wet and rocky landscape to another misty mountainscape.

name: Ek Second...Jo Zindagi Badal de
desc: Badal is a Hindi movie released on 11 February, 2000. The movie is directed by Raj Kanwar  and featured Bobby Deol, Rani Mukherjee and Ashutosh Rana as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Badal are Ashish Vidyarthi, Amrish Puri and Mayuri Kango.

name: Raajneeti
desc: Raajneeti marks the return of twist-and-turn drama to contemporary cinema, which indeed is a refreshing turn of events.

name: Kushti
desc: The high point of the film is Khali's presence in the film. But this one would be quite a disappointment for his fans, because the wrestler has a minuscule cameo that includes a terrible sequence.

name: Admissions Open
desc: This film did have a noble idea. But alas! It has been done so ignobly. The end result is total and terrible confusion.

name: Bumm Bumm Bole
desc: Bumm Bumm Bole is fine vacation fare for the family and presents a viable alternative to parents who are looking for meaningful tween entertainment in a boom-boom age.

name: Badmaash Company
desc: Badmaash Company may not be as buoyant as Bunty aur Babli, the original badmash couple in recent cinema, but it does make for some merry viewing.

name: Housefull
desc: Housefull might not set the summer scorching, but it does create a ripple after a prolonged lull at the multiplexes.

name: City Of Gold
desc: Go and watch 'Spirit of Mumbai' come alive before your eyes in mesmeric form. Kudos to Manjrekar for creating a post-modern Deewar.

name: Muskurake Dekh Zara
desc: Everybody in the film just keeps talking and talking and talking. And what's more irritating is the fact that you can't get a hang of what they are actually debating, discussing, questioning, stating.

name: Bird Idol
desc: Indian animation takes a refreshing turn with Bird Idol, a film which transforms a typical Bollywood masala film into animation and converts the love birds, literally into love birds.

name: Apartment
desc: Apartment's a decent watch provided you promise not to watch Bridget Fonda and Jennifer Jason Leigh do the catfight in Single White Female.

name: Phoonk 2
desc: Phoonk 2 is just another run-of-the-mill horror film and doesn't do anything to lift the genre to another level altogether.

name: Prince
desc: You end up with endless action set pieces, interspersed with a few repetitive soliloquies by sundry people on a stolen coin and a micro chip.

name: Sadiyaan
desc: This one's not only dealing with history, it dabbles with a kind of cinema that seems to have become history too. We haven't got the patience for such euphemisms and moth-balled romances.

name: The Great Indian Butterfly
desc: It breeds some breezy moments of black humour and poignant romance, apart from eliciting some fine performances from the key players.

name: Leaving Home: The Life and Music of Indian Ocean
Prem Kaa Game
desc: Salman Khan tries too hard to add some humour to this humourless film. But nothing seems to work. Confused. Unimaginative. Avoidable.

name: Mittal Vs Mittal
desc: Well-intentioned, yes, but too straight, too talkative and too flag-waving, Mittal versus Mittal is more for the sundry committees on women atrocities than for the new age viewer.

name: Love Sex Aur Dhokha
desc: Dibakar Banerjee's film is meant to be seen -- and savoured -- by shedding all your moth-balled beliefs about how commercial cinema must or must not be.

name: Shaapit
desc: The film works not so much due to its story. Rather, it's the way Vikram Bhatt tells his story - with a certain polish and pizzazz -- that draws you in.

name: Na Ghar Ke Na Ghaat Ke
desc: The intentions are noble. Debutant director, Rahul Aggarwal has a point to make. Nice message. Amateur attempt. Moments of fun.

name: Hide and Seek
desc: After an attempt to revisit Grudge in desi cinema, here's one more Hollywood style slasher film that makes its debut on the native screen. There's enough pizzazz to keep the adrenalin pumping here.

name: Atithi Tum Kab Jaoge?
desc: Neat. Subtle. And softly funny. Atithi Tum Kab Jaoge is quite unlike the hysterical laugh acts that have been trying terribly hard to make you laugh in recent Bollywood.

name: Thanks Maa
desc: Thanks Maa is a film that will make you cry and laugh, even as it fills you with admiration and warmth for the next decrepit kid you see on the red light, running nose et al.

name: Rokkk
desc: There are enough goosebumps in this film to give you your money's worth. You may end up disappointed with the climax which once again concludes with the usual mumbo-jumbo of tantra and mantra.

name: Teen Patti
desc: The film is a taut thriller that's not only done with loads of style and attitude, it also showcases a fine ensemble cast of youngsters who represent the edginess of today's youth.

name: Karthik Calling Karthik
desc: Vijay Lalwani's film is immensely watchable, purely for the class act by Farhan Akhtar in the title role. There is a thrill factor in the film that keeps the momentum on.

name: Toh Baat Pakki
desc: Toh Baat Pakki may not be as riveting as the 80s entertainers, yet it rides high on sheer nostalgia. For those who like their films to move at frenetic pace, the film may seem a bit laidback.

name: Click
desc: The film works only in fits and starts. Watch it for the twist in the tale in the end and some goosebumps in the beginning.

name: My Name Is Khan
desc: My Name is Khan is indubitably one of the most meaningful and moving films to be rolled out from the Bollywood mills in recent times.

name: Phaans: Ek Jasoos Ki Kahani
desc: It's loud, exaggerated, overplayed and spills over with a string of bad performances. Ekdum unbelievable and uncinematic!

name: Ishqiya
desc: In Ishqiya lingo, the film is a sutli bomb (firecracker) that tickles and explodes. But for the hurried and harried end. Go, have a blast.

name: Veer
desc: There's nothing much to hold your attention in this prolonged misadventure that loses a lot due to a tardy screenplay, a headless script and an old-fashioned direction.

name: Pangaa Gang
desc: What could have been a sweet little ode to the environment ends up as a cranky and crude tale of a bunch of kids who team up with the animals to save the forest greens from greedy poachers.

name: Chance Pe Dance
desc: The film may not have the emotional quotient of Ishq Vishq - Shahid and Ken's first film that set the box office on fire, yet it does have its moments.

name: Dulha Mil Gaya
desc: Dulha Mil Gaya works in bits and pieces only and fills you with a sense of wasted opportunity, despite the overt shimmer.

name: Raat Gayi, Baat Gayi?
desc: Watch out for some fine performances by the entire cast. Veterans like Rajat Kapoor, Vinay Pathak and Ranvir Shorey are eminently watchable as always.

name: Bolo Ram
desc: The Jihali angle springs up from nowhere and completely convolutes the film with the subversive use of religious symbolism. Doesn't work.

name: Rocket Singh: Salesman Of The Year
desc: High points of the film are the punchy dialogues and the handful of scenes which touch your heart with their had-enough-of-dishonesty, let's-be-good-now India feel.

name: Kurbaan
desc: Karan Johar’s story has gravitas. Rensil D’Silva’s narrative keeps you on the edge of the seat, for most of the time.

name: Aao Wish Karein
desc: The end product doesn't turn out to be a fairy tale production debut for Aftab. And that's because the film fails to decide its core audience.

name: Tum Mile
desc: Emraan and Soha create a chemistry that is brimming over with warmth and remains quite unpredictable till the very end.

name: Ajab Prem Ki Ghazab Kahani
desc: Gazab comedy, this one. Really, Ranbir is a revelation, Katrina is full of beans and the newly formented Ranbir-Katrina chemistry sets the screen on fire.

name: Jail
desc: Bhandarkar treats his story in a linear fashion and fails to unravel the layers of a drama that proposes to provide a hard look at the interiors of the Indian prison experience.

name: London Dreams
desc: Watch it for the Devgn-Salman thunder and for the simple reason that this is definitely one of Vipul Shah's better films.

name: Aladin
desc: Truly, a big let down from director Sujoy Ghosh who lost both his jhankar and his beats after ‘Home Delivery’ and ‘Aladin’, his films following a scintillating debut with ‘Jhankar Beats’.

name: Bal Ganesh 2
desc: Gannu is back, but isn't really geared to take your breath away. His antics, like the animation, falls flat and the film fails to establish itself as entertainment ammunition for newage kids.

name: All The Best
desc: All the Best offers some rib-tickling moments, but mostly in the second half as the loose plot gradually gives way to complete mayhem.

name: Acid Factory
desc: The film opens on a promising note but loses much of its momentum through a sluggish first half which tends to get repetitive.

name: Fast Forward
desc: Fast Forward comes to life only during the dance sequences. The choreography by Jhalak Dikhla Ja winner Sonia Jaffer Fraser, Seema Desai and Vishnu Deva is both exciting and innovative.

name: What's Your Raashee
desc: A less-than-ruthless editor could have easily trimmed What's Your Raashee by 45 minutes without compromising on its soul. Gowariker seems to have fallen in love with his own work.

name: Ruslaan
desc: Ruslaan neither has the urgency of breaking news nor the perspective of a docu-drama. Film's first half reminds you of the 1970s family socials and is good enough to give a headache to even a Saridon.

name: Bachelor Party
desc: Bachelor Party is coarse comedy. The problem is that all the risqué gags notwithstanding, the movie is simply not funny enough.

name: Aagey Se Right
desc: The film is loaded with puns: ustra becomes tu is tarah and rukhsat becomes rook nahin sakti. And smart one-liners: socha to locha. But the film never becomes the intelligent comedy it intends to be.

name: Mohandas
desc: Mohandas isn't what is vulgarly called "timepass". It isn't the sort of movie that soothes. But it is engaging and gripping for the larger part.

name: Three - Love, Lies and Betrayal
desc: Movie's biggest drawback is that its actors neither have box-office pull nor the charm to hold attention. Three just falls short of being a three-star affair.

name: Chintu Ji
desc: Sadly, Chintuji is a case of good intentions marred by flawed execution. The first half speaks the language of community; the second half is personality oriented. The switch jars.

name: Daddy Cool
desc: What works partially in film's favour is its high-pitched energy. Director K Muralimohana Rao doesn't let the pace slacken in the first half though a readymade template would have simplified his life.

name: Quick Gun Murugan
desc: You cannot blame director Shashanka Ghosh and writer Rajesh Devraj for not trying something different. They are bang on with the movie's looks. Too bad, the team fails to create its soul.

name: Love Khichdi
desc: Love Khichdi has style, wit and that dirty five-letter word, heart. Trimming it by 15 minutes would have made it crisper. Nonetheless, it's a swell date flick.

name: Shadow
desc: If there's something that's clear in this blurred Shadow, it's Naseer Khan, who despite being physically challenged in real life manages to carry out stunts with ease and confidence in reel life.

name: Sikandar
desc: Watch it for the special bonding between the tussi-ja-rahe-ho charmer (of Kuch Kuch Hota Hai fame) turned into a curious teen with a dark side, Parzan.

name: Kaminey
desc: Vishal Bhardwaj not only gives you a crackling screenplay, brimming over with smart one-liners, he creates cameos that stay with you long after curtain call.

name: Teree Sang
desc: This one's a breezy take on teenage romance which draws its charm from the performances. But the film fails to highlight the trauma of teen pregnancy in a closed society.

name: Agyaat
desc: This one's a big disappointment from a director who has already proved his forte with the horror genre with goosebump films like Bhoot and Raat. It is completely devoid of the fear factor.

name: Luck
desc: Luck is so heavy on style, it seems to completely forget about the script. So much so, the film is like one extended reality show.

name: Jashnn
desc: Watch it for its vintage appeal: it reminds you of the unadulterated emotional interplay of Mahesh Bhatt's cinema, not so long ago.

name: Dekh Re Dekh
desc: 'Dekh Re Dekh' begins on an interesting premise and even catapults strange new characters before a formula-fed audience. Yet, it fails to sustain the dark humour and peters off before the climax.

name: Short Kut: The Con Is On
Sankat City
desc: The film may have a raw look and lack technical finesse, but don't be fooled. For Sankat City is a roller-coaster ride through downtown Mumbai with its chota-mota crime and its chatpata characters.

name: Kambakkht Ishq
desc: Surely, it take more than Jimmy Choo, Prada, Versace and LA to make a film that can tickle and entertain. Million dollar looks and a multi-crore budget can't make up for characters and a kahaani.

name: Paying Guests
desc: It's a completely chaotic story that keeps hurtling towards doom from the word go. Presumably a comedy, the film actually ends up making you cry.

name: Kal Kissne Dekha
desc: Neither the story nor the debut kids (Jackky Bhagnani and Vaishali Desai) have much to offer in this strange mish-mash of romance and terrorism.

name: Karma: Crime, Passion, Reincarnation
desc: The story may be archaic, but the film carries you along with its thriller pace, its twist in the tale and the visual splendour of splendid Ooty.

name: Anubhav
desc: The only thing that holds the film together is a fine act by Sanjay Suri who tries to invest some dignity in this film that borders on the crude.

name: Yeh Pal Ho Na Ho...Kal
desc: It's a film where nobody acts. Everybody hams. And everything goes haywire, including the moth-balled dialogues about sati and pati.

name: Partition
desc: The director completely relegates actors like Irrfan Khan and Vinay Pathak to stand-bys in one or two scenes. Sheer waste.

name: Ocean of an Old Man
desc: It's an introspective piece of work which needs to be viewed patiently. The aftermath of the tsunami seems to have raised a million questions which the film movingly throws up.

name: Sanam Teri Kasam
desc: The plot is as convoluted as the going-nowhere romances of the 1990s. Somersault time for us too, unless you'd like to watch Pooja wilting, Saif sobbing and Atul sleepwalking.
This crime-and-comic caper not only flits between the present and the past, it also switches between Mumbai and Delhi. But always with the unpredictable, threatening to explode round the corner.

name: Antaheen
desc: The pressure of love, career, urban loneliness- all build up to a stunning climax, which leaves you riveted till the end. A moody, languorous and extremely artistic look at life in a metro.

name: Frozen
desc: The film's a tryst with pure cinema, in terms of its scintillating cinematography and lays down a strong plea for peace and harmony. Go for a different experience.

name: Chowrasta Crossroads of Love
desc: The film may be low on high drama but the director manages to create a mesmerising mood and draws you into the play of emotions that unfolds with a lazy charm.

name: Coffee House
desc: The film scores mostly in its performances by actors who may not be big stars but are big in talent. Don't go looking for regular naach-gana and gloss and you will find substance and a soul.

name: School Days
desc: Brimming over with several heart-tugging moments, the film does fall a bit short in terms of finesse and production values.

name: 8x10 Tasveer
desc: Though the film is based on an unusual premise and focuses on a new hero-type, the plot simply plods along, with undue repetition and the sci-fi biz is just a ploy to peddle a regular whodunit.

name: Ek: The Power of One
desc: Watch it only if you want to see what old-fashioned Bollywood looked like, before the smart new wave swept away the cobwebs.

name: Aa Dekhen Zara
desc: It's a smart new concept, a snazzy coupling between Neil and Bipasha and a thriller's edge that keeps Aa Dekhen Zara cruising along.

name: Videsh
desc: Magical potions, mythical make-believe, a melodramatic climax, 'Videsh' completely loses its connect with the urban viewer.

name: Straight
desc: Low key and light-hearted, the film cruises along untrodden paths, with Vinay Pathak cementing his place as a tedha-medha (read unconventional) actor who successfully dares to go solo.

name: Firaaq
desc: The film is a balanced, sensitive documentation of contemporary India's most trying times and posits a much-needed plea for sanity, peace and tolerance.

name: Gulaal
desc: Anurag Kashyap leaves behind the 'emotional atyachar' of 'Dev D' for an equally violent and chaotic world of student politics in 'Gulaal'.

name: Little Zizou
desc: What stands out are the life-like performances by the ensemble cast — the kids are brilliant — and the gentle comic strain that carries the film forward with a chuckle and a grin. Don't miss it.

name: Karma Aur Holi
desc: This film's a teaser that leaves you completely foxed. While it's easy to understand about the Holi bit in the title but there's just nothing to explain the Karma adjunct.

name: 13B
desc: Watch '13B' for some zippy cinematography, a stylised monochrome tint and some snazzy editing. Great timepass. Go for it.

name: Dhoondte Reh Jaoge
desc: True. 'Dhoondte hi reh jaoge', for that side-splitting comedy that's supposed to give you paisa-vasool entertainment.

name: Siddharth: The Prisoner
desc: A metaphorical story about freedom and desire, the film keeps you engrossed by its explorations on the leitmotif of greed and due to Rajat Kapoor's nuanced, almost minimalist act of a man in torment.

name: Jugaad
desc: The film is well-intentioned and has an honest core to it. Nevertheless, the drama gets repetitive and loses its bite.

name: Billu
desc: Director Priyadarshan has suitably peppered it with some heart-tugging moments to make it a moving ode to friendship and ordinariness.

name: The Stoneman Murders
desc: Set against the serial killings that terrorised the pavement dwellers of Mumbai in 1983, the film is a neat little thriller which actually keeps you glued to your seats.

name: Chal Chala Chal
desc: You almost feel sorry for Govinda, who doesn't really need to spoil his career graph with inconsequential stuff like 'Chal Chala Chal'.

name: Dev D
desc: Dev D is one such flight of fancy from the filmmaker that definitely defies all conventions and demolishes all moulds.

name: Luck By Chance
desc: The jibes are gentle, the tenor is fond, yet firm. But most importantly, the characters are completely real: feisty and flawed, even as the end is exhilarating.

name: Victory
desc: Go for some cricket dhamaka and for Hurman's second coming which seems to make Love Story 2050 seem like a nightmare.

name: Aasma
desc: The film lacks all energy. Quite sad especially since the film did try to say something about so many things - about the joy of theatre, the power of friendship, the will to triumph.

name: Raaz—The Mystery Continues
desc: Director Mohit Suri does manage to get his groove back a bit, after a series of insignificant films. Watch it for a couple of goosebumps, here and there.

name: Chandni Chowk To China
desc: The film is low on both IQ and EQ. On the one hand, the story rambles incoherently. On the other, there is no emotional connect with any of the characters, unlike Akshay's earlier comic acts.

name: Jumbo
desc: The animation has definitely improved, with the animals, the humans and the backdrop forming a picturesque collage, the story is completely outdated and the narration tedious.

name: Wafaa
desc: You'll have to suffer a senseless film about a sex-starved woman who keeps taunting her rich and plump husband (Rajesh Khanna) for his inadequacies.

name: Dil Kabaddi
desc: The film begins on a promising note and then peters off into repetitive scenes, some funny, some silly, where nothing actually happens.

name: Maharathi
desc: If you want a taste of a desi version of Sleuth, Peter Shaffer's spellbinding play-turned-film, go watch Maharathi. The story may be different, the edge of danger is almost similar.

name: Oye Lucky! Lucky Oye!
desc: Director Dibakar Banerjee knows Delhi, complete with its underbelly and recreates the class divide with great artistry.

name: Sorry Bhai!
desc: Sorry Bhai is a delightful film that comes alive, solely on the power-packed performances of its parallel brigade: actors who live beyond the parameters of the traditional star system.

name: Yuvvraaj
desc: Subhash Ghai returns with Yuvvraaj, a grandiose film that has lots to boast about, even though it falters here and there in terms of script and narrative. Watch Yuvvraaj for an in-fashion retro feel.

name: Desh Drohi
desc: We can't understand why Mr KRK (Kamal Rashid Khan) dreamt of doing an SRK especially since he doesn't know the ABC of acting.

name: Dasvidaniya
desc: The heart and soul of the film undoubtedly is Vinay Pathak, who reinvents the quiet, submissive common man, already dead with the weight of his dull, uneventful life.

name: Dostana
desc: Just for laughs, with a loose second half, Dostana boasts of some fine chemistry between the two lead players: Abhishek and John.

name: Ek Vivah Aisa Bhi
desc: Every twist and turn in this sister's sacrificial story is predictable. The only thing that works are the performances.

name: EMI
desc: There's nothing that works in this film, not even Urmila Matondkar as the woman who wants her husband's life insurance and engages hoodlums to get her due. Nor Sanjay Dutt, in a fleeting appearance.

name: Golmaal Returns
desc: Golmaal Returns is a Hindi movie released on 29 October, 2008. The movie is directed by Rohit Shetty  and featured Ajay Devgn, Arshad Warsi and Amrita Arora as lead characters. Other popular actors who were roped in for Golmaal Returns are Kareena Kapoor Khan.

name: Fashion
desc: The film desperately needs some tight editing to cut out the flab. Nevertheless, go, witness woman power, in all its agony and ecstasy.

name: Roadside Romeo
desc: Watch out this film for the beautiful climax and for some state-of-the-art animation that hadn't reached desi cinema till now.

name: Heroes
desc: This film does have flashes of fine storytelling and some noteworthy performances. Could have worked, but for the high decibel intonation of patriotism which works best when it is played out softly.

name: Karzzz
desc: If you are looking for pure masala, with no pretensions of brainy-brawny stuff, then go for this film. You could get your paisa vasool.

name: Cheenti Cheenti Bang Bang
desc: This is the first Indian animation film with some great voice-overs. But Indian animation still has miles to go before we can have our desi Antz and A Bug's Life.

name: Shoot On Sight
desc: Set against the London bombings of 2005, the film is a sensitive, high voltage diatribe against both terrorism as well as racial profiling.

name: Hello
desc: The film slips from intermittent smartness to overriding sloppiness. The only thing that holds Hello together are the performances, specially by Sharman Joshi and Sohail Khan.

name: Kidnap
desc: This thriller film may be low on Dhoom this time, but young Imran Khan more than makes up for the sluggish pace and the mediocre script.

name: Hari Puttar
