desc: The third part in the fantasy series holds merit on its own and manages to hold you in your seat with its mix of make-believe, special effects and fairy tale folklore.

name: Secretariat
desc: The real drama picks up only in the final few moments of the movie when Secretariat, steals the show with with his racing moments. Exciting yet predictable.

name: Unstoppable
desc: The film does move on predictable lines, nevertheless, the well-crafted sound and action sequences make the film worth a visit.

name: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 1
From Paris With Love
desc: James Reece , an aide to the US ambassador in Paris, has just got engaged to a beautiful French girl, Caroline and would like to spend the rest of the week serenading her.

name: The Other Guys
desc: Light and breezy, The Other Guys is your cop house comedy which runs through a familiar track where fifteen minutes of fame do come, but only when our common man types have been tried and tested.

name: Letters to Juliet
desc: Set against the breathtaking scenery of the Tuscan backdrop, Letters to Juliet is a love story that makes you want to believe in the legend of Romeo and Juliet.

name: Eat Pray Love
desc: The film manages to carry you through its cross-country journey, peppered with scenic locales and attention-grabbing characters, the credit for which goes to Julia Roberts.

name: Beauty And the Beast
desc: There's the sublime beauty of a forgotten world and the promise of happily-ever-after to draw you to one of your favourite fairy tales, once again. Give it an encore.

name: A Distant Mirage
desc: Sadly, there isn't enough -- neither story, nor performances -- to sustain a decent run for A Distant Mirage. Too much has already been said on the issue.

name: Crank: High Voltage
desc: The filmmakers don't seem to be taking themselves seriously. Neither should we. So all you diehard action buffs can take a chance with Crank 2. It is high voltage action, albeit with a jaded edge.

name: Shanghai
desc: The drama might not engage you with its heavy political overtones, its outdated tenor and its overriding seriousness. But the star cast definitely will.

name: Resident Evil: Afterlife
desc: All the alpha and brawn show doesn't stop your attention wavering mid-film when testosterone is side-tracked for testy, long drawn conversation.

name: Avatar:Special Edition
desc: You can hardly spot the difference between the old and the new Avatar, unless you've studied it minutely and seen it several times in its first edition.

name: Cats and Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
Dinner for Schmucks
desc: Fun while it lasts, Dinner For Schmucks is a black comedy that is paced out and restrained. No loud laughs here. Just gentle chuckles.

name: The Expendables
desc: Don't go looking for a script. Just settle down for some vintage bang-bang stuff where guns were supposed to speak louder than special effects and guys had nothing to fall back on.

name: Grown Ups
desc: Savour the Sandler brand of humour with Grown Ups, a film that once again celebrates the spirit of childhood, like most of his comedies.

name: Despicable Me
desc: Despicable Gru (Steve Carell) has just one ambition. He wants to be the perfect anti-hero and showcase some super villainy. And how does he propose to do so? By stealing the moon. But before he can do that, he must steal into the house of the evil nerd, Vector (Jason Segal) and foil his attempts at a million dollar heist. For this, he needs to adopt three cute orphans from Miss Hattie's Home for Girls. The beginning of the transformation of Superbad Gru to Superdad Gru!

name: Salt
desc: It's Angelina Jolie, all the way. She's extremely watchable as the female agent who commendably stands up to the Bond and Bourne Inc.

name: The Sorcerer's Apprentice
desc: This one's a simple summer flick that keeps the popcorn crisp. However, the story isn't original and does fill you with a sense of deja vu.

name: Knight and Day
desc: The action is completely over the top. And the film is such a chaloo cheeseburst, you just can't miss it. Go, sink your teeth in it.

name: Spread
desc: Watch it for Ashton Kutcher and his pretty boy charms. And also for his existential dilemma: to be a gigolo or a grocery boy.

name: Toy Story 3
desc: There is colour, verve, drama, action, comedy, romance and 3D too. Add to this, a few wonderful take-home morals for our young and old viewers, and what more can you want.

name: The A-Team
desc: The A-Team is strictly for action buffs who love to OD on high-decibel AXN cuts. The action is superbly crafted, leaving no room for anything else.

name: The Karate Kid
desc: The film has a lot to offer to young adults, but fails to rise to cult status. And that's only because the martial arts display is somewhat marginalised by the drama and relationship building.

name: Robin Hood
desc: Go watch this version, because the sequel is bound to follow. And then, we are sure, all hell will break lose....Savour the lull before the storm.

name: Sex and the City 2
desc: The sequel may not be as spunky as the first film, yet, Sex and the City 2 has enough to keep the cosmo club grinning.

name: Nightmare on ELM Street
desc: The new version may not be a revisionist tale and has nothing new to offer but it does have some old fashioned scares that still work.

name: Shutter Island
desc: This one's a gritty drama, with Scorsese creating some marvellous set pieces where the past intervenes with the present and Leonardo creates a compelling picture of brooding disarray.

name: Brick Lane
desc: Watch the film for the grandeur that both Satish Kaushik and Tannishtha Chatterjee invest in their role of the low key couple who try to cope with a changing world order.

name: Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time
desc: The high point of the film is its stellar ensemble cast headed by Ben Kingsley who lends gravitas to the entire proceedings as Nizam, the King's brother.

name: Daybreakers
desc: This one's for those who still haven't had their fill of vampire lore which happens to be the current craze in Hollywood and those who like their vampires mostly mean and monster-like.

name: Shrek Forever After
desc: Go watch your favourite ogre live out the ugly-is-beautiful revisionist tale, once again. And make you feel good about it.

name: Remember Me
desc: Set against 9/11, Remember Me is an immensely watchable romance, even as it paints a touching picture of loss and redemption against a violence-scarred backdrop. Raise a toast for RPatz.

name: The Back-Up Plan
desc: It may be nothing to rave about, yet, The Back-Up Plan is good while it lasts, with Jennifer Lopez managing to hold your attention with her attempt at motherhood.

name: The Last Song
desc: The highpoint of the film are the special moments created by Greg Kinnear and Miley Cyrus as they develop a warm and tender father-daughter relationship. Let them tug at your heart.

name: Iron Man 2
desc: The sequel is one hellish and hungama-filled ride into the world of high-octane drama. It may lack the finesse of the first film, but there's enough to keep the adrenalin pumping.

name: Hot Tub Time Machine
desc: The retro scenes do have a comic feel to it, nevertheless, Hot Tub Time Machine lacks the panache of time travel films like Back To The Future. The laughs too come in fits and starts.

name: Astro boy
desc: Astro Boy, with its colourful animation and its dramatic voice-overs is perfect weekend fare for kids who need a break from the violent games on play station.

name: The Bounty Hunter
desc: Funny in places, feisty here and there, The Bounty Hunter, is one more middle-of-the-road outing from Jennifer Aniston.

name: Cop Out
desc: It's crude. It's rude. And it's downright funny, but only in a down and out way. Enjoy the nonsensical, one evening.

name: Green Zone
desc: Don't go looking for the Bourne effect and you'll enjoy the relevance of this film which dares to question and debate.

name: Date Night
desc: The Fosters, a boring couple from New Jersey, go on a routine date to a high end, overbooked restaurant in Manhattan. When they don't get place, they steal someone else's reservation and end up being chased by trigger-happy gangsters and corrupt cops who want them to deliver a stolen flash drive. Can the Fosters, now mistaken as the Triplehorns, deliver and get back to their staid, suburban domesticity?

name: The Hurt Locker
desc: Don't miss this topical teaser of a film that dares to go inside the mind of the young soldier who is herded into the battle field, without actually knowing why.

name: Vicky Cristina Barcelona
desc: The highpoint of the film is the unstable equilibrium the three women try to establish in their interactions with the Don Juan. Penelope Cruz is simply riveting.

name: Gamer
desc: Meant strictly for action-buffs, Gamer is a timely warning for the gaming industry. Too much virtual violence might just turn the real world turtle.

name: The Book of Eli
desc: The film is essentially an extremely well-shot action drama embellished with some fine performances by Denzel Washington and Gary Oldman.

name: New in Town
desc: An inconsequential love story, New in Town acquires body and form only because of Ms Zellweger. Watch it as time-pass. It could make you smile on an average day.

name: Nine
desc: Nine may not be as engrossing as Rob Marshall's other mind-bending musical, Chicago. Nevertheless, it is an enchanting experience with Daniel Day Lewis.

name: Alice In Wonderland
desc: The evergreen fable comes alive in mesmeric form. Don't miss your tryst with a dapper Johnny Depp, a newage Alice and an over-the-top Tim Burton.

name: Love Happens
desc: This one's serious business. Much of the romance between Jennifer Aniston and Aaron Eckhart proceeds on a sombre note, with both our protagonists trying to cope with their personal tragedies.

name: Percy Jackson And The Olympians: The Lightning Thief
desc: Young Percy Jackson is a demi-god (son of a god and a human). He is falsely accused of stealing the lightning bolt and must retrieve it before earth is torn asunder by the warring gods. Aiding him in his search for the missing bolt are Annabeth, the daughter of goddess Athena and Satyr, a half-human, half-goat creature.

name: Up In The Air
desc: A smart script, great performances, witticisms galore, Up In The Air is a humanist document of today's times. Not to be missed at all.

name: Valentine's Day
desc: The film doesn't quite live up to Garry Marshall's rendition of the Cinderella myth in Pretty Woman, but it fits in with the mood of the moment.

name: Old Dogs
desc: Watch out for moments of fun in this routine comedy. Both John Travolta and Robin Williams crackle, despite their aging and weathering.

name: Coco Avant Chanel
desc: Watch the film for its character sketch, its authenticity and for a towering performance by Audrey Tautou in the eponymous role.

name: Bruno
desc: The film may not be as uproarious as Borat but it does give you some rollicking moments with Sacha Baron Cohen unleashing his manic energy once again. Enjoy, the adult way.

name: New York I love you
desc: The film, written by the late Anthony Minghella, is sheer visual poetry, with its white interiors and its hazy outlines.

name: The Spy Next Door
desc: Nothing original and not quite quintessential Chan -- the action here is muted -- this one's only for diehard Jackie buffs.

name: Case 39
desc: As a film, Case 39 does work at the simple, basic level of a thriller that thrills. Although Ms Zellweger does look somewhat jaded and whispers a bit too much to create her characteristic impact.

name: Did You Hear About the Morgans?
desc: The film does have a tired Hugh Grant and a washed out Sarah Jessica Parker trying to be funny. To be fair, they do manage to make you smile, now and then, while the popcorn lasts.

name: Paranormal Activity
desc: Catch the night show if you actually want to feel the heebie-jeebies. And don't go looking for long-winded explanations. You might end up blaming the chill, not on winter alone.

name: Avatar
desc: James Cameron chooses to play God and creates a whole new world with such exquisite finesse, aesthete and eye for detail, he almost takes your breath away.

name: Tinker Bell and The Lost Treasure
desc: This one's a perfect outing for the kids who will have a ball watching the pesky Trolls, taking the 21 butterfly salute or savouring the Fairy Tale Theatre orchestra made up of frogs and crickets.

name: Ninja Assassin
desc: The fight sequences are the highlight of this film. But it has its emotional core too as it captures the angst of young Raizo who tries to quell the thundering of his heart in a heartless world.

name: A Christmas Carol
desc: Loads of special effects and a story that has stood the test of time: Christmas Carol is Carrey revisited. However, it's not really a children's film and is meant for diehard Dicken's fans.

name: Twilight
desc: The film actually works because it sculpts a romance that blooms through self-denial and renunciation. Grab your munchies and go for it!
What really holds your attention is apocalypse itself. Yes, it's the special effects of the film, more than the human drama, which completely sweep you off your feet.

name: Whiteout
desc: The film fails to exploit the exotic locales of the South Pole and the twists and turns are mostly predictable in this tundra thriller which is based on a graphic novel by Greg Rucka.

name: This Is It
desc: Go where you've never been before. Witness the concert that might have been. Experience the magic of a man who made you jump over the moon.

name: Shorts
desc: Just the lack of hi-tech special effects and the chaotic structure of the story which lurches back through a series of disjointed flashbacks. That's where you might end up blinking! Fun, nevertheless.

name: Taking woodstock
desc: For those who'd like to decipher why the hippie cult was so alluring to the earth-bound, Taking Woodstock is low-key yet lyrical.

name: Surrogates
desc: Watch out for the action sequences and Bruce Willis trying to replay some of Arnold Schwarzenneger's Terminator magic.

name: Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs
desc: Occasionally funny and inventive, CWCM is like a great-looking dish that only intermittently gets as tasty as it looks.

name: District 9
desc: Disturbingly powerful visual effects and a dark background score add to the film's appeal. Worth a viewing but make sure you only catch the English version.

The machines turned against humans and annihilated them. But they too were largely destroyed. The challenge of reviving civilization falls on a band of 'small creations' who fight the few surviving brutal machines

name: The Final Destination
desc: State-of-art technology must upgrade a good narrative but cannot act as its substitute. Sadly, The Final Destination tries precisely that.

name: The Brothers Bloom
desc: There's loads of twists and turns on this road full of bumpy rides. Of course, with ample fun en route! So just in case you feel being taken for a ride is in right now, go for it.

name: G.I. Joe: Rise of the Cobra
desc: If non-stop action thrills is what you're looking for and we don't really mind a rather not-so-packed storyline, it's time to join the G.I. Joe heroes.

name: Ghosts of Girlfriends Past
desc: Just in case you like a romcom that tugs at your heart strings, there's loads of senti speeches, overwhelming cuteness, romantic-realisation-of-love moments and tender touches.

name: Public Enemies
desc: The film is a cinematic treat with its artistic canvas, its fine detailing and its towering portrayal of a real-life bandit by Johnny Depp.

name: Red Cliff
desc: Don't go looking for Zhang Yimou's period epics; nor expect the anti-gravity athleticism of Crouching Tiger Hidden Dragon and you might just be mesmerised by John Woo's grandiose battles.

name: Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian
Boarding Gate
desc: The clock keeps ticking in this taut thriller that doesn't really boast of anything original, other than Ms Asia and her antics.

name: Harry Potter And The Half-Blood Prince
The Proposal
desc: It may be unabashedly sentimental and predictably romantic, yet The Proposal manages to win you over with its sassy script and showstopper Sandra.

name: Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs
The Hangover
desc: A great fun ride, The Hangover introduces a whole new bunch of talent to Hollywood, specially Zach, the nerd. Don't miss it.

name: Bolt
desc: Now this one's a fun film for the entire family, with little lessons on love and friendship you can carry home with you. Lessons you learn from a dog, a cat and a hamster.

name: Bride Wars
desc: Feminists would surely bare their fangs at this one, which sees the girls stooping to silly lows in their game of come-uppance. But the rest might just find it silly and funny. Take your pick.

name: Angels and Demons
desc: Angels and Demons is one of the most engrossing masala films from current Hollywood. We bet you'll forget your popcorns too!

name: Chocolate
desc: Go for the adrenalin-pumping action sequences which are pure art, in terms of their perfect hand-foot-eye coordination. The film reminds you of Tarantino's hand combat tricks in the Kill Bill series.

name: Cabin Fever
desc: Watch it, if you can handle the preponderance of red -- oodles and oodles of blood dripping from the screen, with scenes of stomach-churning muck that's definitely not meant for the faint-hearted.

name: New Police Story 5
desc: Watch out for regular Chan fare, which includes some dizzy action sequences and high-octane chases that never seem to tire the action junkie in you.

name: Pride and Glory
desc: Edward Norton, the good NYPD cop, tries to bust a drug deal and comes up with startling evidence that implicates his family. His elder brother, Noah Emmerich and brother-in-law, Colin Farrell may also be cops, but their record isn't clean.

name: The Year My Parents Went on Vacation
desc: Watch it for its alluring recreation of the life and times of the ordinary Brazilian who attains nirvana with Pele's magical footwork and for its powerful performances.

name: Watchmen
desc: Watchmen isn't as hard-hitting and stomach-churning as 300, nevertheless it creates a canvas of stirring images and enigmatic characters that keep you riveted.

name: Elegy
desc: Watch it for the rich fabric and the intense chemistry between Ben Kingsley and Penelope Cruz who set the screen on fire with their passion and anguish.

name: One Man Army
desc: The film's a visual delight for martial arts buffs and is a waft of fresh breeze in the overcrowded world of chopsucky cinema.

name: Fast and Furious 4
desc: There is the enigmatic characterisation of Vin Diesel as the good-bad Dom, who keeps you guessing about his ethics till the very end. Get your testosterone kick.

name: The Class
desc: The film is a must for all educationalists as it brings to light a whole new system of education where interactivity is the key word.

name: Anywhere But Home
desc: What's missing in this film is both warmth and humour. The gags are too loud and the bonding too clinical to actually make you a believer too, like the protagonists who forget fun in Fiji for family.

name: Underworld lll: Rise of the Lycans
desc: Watch the film for its special effects and its cinematography which lends an eerie, grey chill to the high-voltage action sequences between weird creatures.

name: Confessions of a Shopaholic
desc: Watch the film for a zany comic act by Isla Fisher who almost perfects the role of the ditzy chick who ain't as dumb as you think.

name: The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants 2
desc: This is essentially a more serious version of Sex and the City, where the protagonists are younger, their concerns are more real and their journey towards self-realisation strikes a deeper chord.

name: Gran Torino
desc: Uplifting, topical and absolutely engaging, Gran Torino posits an answer to the current clash-of-cultures theory that seems to have sent the new world in a tizzy.

name: Talk To Me
desc: A biopic based on the life of Petey Greene (Don Cheadle), a convict who became a legendary DJ and TV talk show artist, the film is a compelling story of individual atonement.

name: Street Kings
desc: Intelligently paced, with enough thrills to keep the adrenalin pumping, Street Kings unleashes the Keanu charisma after a long time.

name: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
desc: It's a long, meandering film which keeps you engrossed with its hard-hitting performances and its intricate eye for detail.

name: Out of Bounds
desc: Does money justify a dehumanised life? 'Out of Bounds' has won requisite applause at sundry international film festivals for addressing this question with style and sensitivity.

name: Turtles Can Fly
desc: The film leaves you devastated with its chilling climax and shakes you out of your stupor, even as it overawes you with its powerful imagery of the wasteland that is war. Don't miss it..

name: Emotional Arithmetic
desc: Watch it for the unresolved equations and questions that must definitely mar the life of any and every one who survives a violent act of history.

name: The Curious Case of Benjamin Button
desc: Based on a story by F Scott Fitzgerald, the film is essentially a fantasy that recreates the flavour of Forrest Gump. Watch the film for it's curious flavour.

name: Valkyrie
desc: While Hitler largely figures as a silhouette in the film, it is Tom Cruise who remains as the tormented military man with a conscience that precluded him from raising his hand to 'Hail Hitler!'

name: Milk
desc: Watch it for an unforgettable performance by Sean Penn who is heroic in his ordinariness, proving that outliers and high-flyers are made, not born.

name: What Just Happened
desc: Recipe enough for loads of drama that keeps the entertainment meter alive and kicking. But not really something you'd expect from Raging Bull, Robert DeNiro.

name: He's just not that into you
desc: This one's sheer candy floss, meant for a Valentine viewing. Don't go looking for heart-tugging romance and you won't end up disappointed.

name: Redline
desc: Despite a poor plot, there's enough in this movie to keep the testosterone-filled spirits upbeat, specially for speed addicts and auto freaks with the rollicking car parade.

name: Seven Pounds
desc: Seven Pounds is a sincerely told, mushy tale about spreading good cheer and making the world a better place, with Smith essaying the role of the tormented do-gooder with impeccable zeal.

name: How To Lose Friends and Alienate People
desc: The film is a witty adaptation of journalist Toby Young's autobiographical account of the years he spent at Vanity Fair and his brush with Page 3 journalism.

name: Outlander
desc: Nothing outlandish about this one, specially if you've seen the more evolved versions of alien monsters, like Predator and Species.

name: Honeydripper
desc: Like a rich and fading tapestry, the film successfully manages to create a lost world, a lost time. That we may never forget.

name: Meet Bill
desc: Camp fires, crackers, pyjama parties coupled with some hardballed fisticuffs is all it takes to make befuddled Bill come of age. Only, the fun parts seem to elude the viewer completely in this meandering, plotless venture.

name: Bedtime Stories
desc: He's the archetypal Mr Under-Appreciated by now. For Adam Sandler has never really digressed from his first few roles of the affable underdog that made him a household name, some years ago.

name: Slumdog Millionaire
desc: Slumdog Millionaire is just a piece of riveting cinema, meant to be savoured as a Cinderella-like fairy tale, with the edge of a thriller and the vision of an artist.

name: I'm Not There
desc: For those who are hoping to find a straight biopic about the legendary singer, this one's definitely not the ‘Once there was Robert Allen Zimmerman aka Bob Dylan' kinda thing.

name: Flashbacks of a Fool
desc: Baillie Walsh's this dramatic film begins on a promising note. As the opening credits start rolling, the music played in the background soothes your heart and the visuals of the enchanting friendship shared between two young boys make you nostalgic.

name: Changeling
desc: The film has been directed as a detailed period piece about an age when no one thought of photographic evidence or DNA testing.This one falls short of Eastwood's other highs.

name: The President Is Coming
desc: The film has a raw look and lacks finesse when it comes to production values. But there is a delightful tongue-in-cheek tenor running through it, which makes you overlook the unpolished feel and the loose editing.

name: Australia
desc: Set against the tumult of World War ll, the director shifts his drama to Australia, complete with it's characteristic slangs, lingo, cows, horses, farming, landscape, aborigines, celebrations and folktales.

name: Outsourced
desc: Life's a relentless question mark for products salesman Todd Anderson (Josh Hamilton) when he is sent to India to train his replacement.

name: In Bruges
desc: It's a smart gangster film, with some high powered acting by Colin Farrell as the conscience-stricken, suicidal hitman who has killed a small boy on his first assignment.

name: Razzle Dazzle
desc: What really keeps glittering in this razzle dazzle of reality shows is Darren Ashton’s own chicken curry for the soul.

name: Madagascar 2: Escape to Africa
desc: This film is charming, with eye-popping visuals, vibrant animation, rib-tickling teasers and a joyous abandon that makes for perfect tweeny fare.

name: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
desc: High School Musical 3 follows a similar storyline where a bunch of drama school undergrads must put up a musical before they go their separate ways.

name: In The Name of the King
desc: Set in a strange era -- the kingdom of Ehb -- where kings were poisoned and evil magicians ruled, the film has a dark, sepia tone that doesn't quite match up to the visual splendour.

name: The Page Turner
desc: This film is a taut French thriller that treats the leitmotif of revenge like vintage wine that grows more heady with age.

name: The Hunting Party
desc: It's a gritty, nerve-wracking thriller that sees unusual threesome -- seasoned journos, Gere and Howard and Harvard graduate, greenhorn Eisenberg -- embark on a do-or-die mission. So get your thrills.

name: The Day the Earth Stood Still
desc: The film is essentially a re-make of a 1951 film and traces the journey of an alien, Klaatu (Keanu Reeves) in New York.

name: Still Life
desc: Based on the real life Three Gorges Dam Project on the Yangste River which demolished the entire ancient town of Fenjgie, the camera accompanies the two protagonists - a coal mine worker and a nurse.

name: Burn After Reading
desc: Burn After Reading is an arresting piece of a crime-gone-awry drama with an unconventional act by both George Clooney and Brad Pitt who discover their negative shades with apblomb.

name: Transporter 3
desc: The Transporter is back. This time with a human cargo: the kidnapped Natalya Rudakova who needs to be delivered to her father, a high-ranking Ukaranian government official.

name: Nights in Rodanthe
desc: The script is stale, the narrative tardy. What works is the chemistry of Diane Lane and Richard Gere which has already been displayed in two films, "The Unfaithful" and "The Cotton Club".

name: Max Payne
desc: "Max Payne" lives up to the video gaming formula and offers loads of action, drama, violence, albeit with characters that need no joystick to explode.

name: Eagle Eye
desc: All sound and fury, signifying nothing new! That's the trouble with this new flick on terrorism, where once again America is in danger, with the President and his entire cabinet being the target of attack.

name: 2 Days in Paris
desc: Brimming over with delightful one-liners on clash of cultures, gender differences, sexual mores, the film is a charmer.

name: Quantum of Solace
desc: There's one big problem with this 22nd Bond film. It has been severely depleted of the quantum of Bondness that made this franchise so special, so irresistible, so debonair.

name: Days Of Glory
desc: This film documents the heroism of those soldiers who fought shoulder to shoulder with the white men, but were denied equality.

name: Body of Lies
desc: Almost every film taking on the terrorist these days. But when you have Leornado DiCaprio on special operations to nab the Al Qaeda jihadis, terrorist hunting becomes special.

name: Star Wars: The Clone Wars
desc: Why would anyone want to replace the live action histrionics of the iconic Star Wars series with strangely animated creatures who can not create SFX magic of the Lucas pedigree.

name: Miss Pettigrew Lives For A Day
desc: Bharat Nalluri has created waves with his debut venture - a wacky comedy that re-creates the 1940s in London, even as it unfolds like a sweet, lyrical fairy tale about love and ever-after.

name: The Edge of Heaven
desc: Nejat, a Turkish professor who teaches German in a German university finds his life changing after his father brings in a Turkish hooker into the house.

name: Hellboy ll: The Golden Army
desc: That's the comic book hero Hellboy for you, who has his second outing under Guillermo Del Toro's creative expertise, and ends up better than his first avtar.

name: The Strangers
desc: Liv Tyler and Scott Speedman return from the woods to their home to resolve an unfinished quarrel but three strange, masked figures threaten to break into their house, for no reason at all.

name: Charlie Bartlett
desc: 17-year-old Charlie Bartlett is a worthy heir to Caulfield's rebellious teen angst in this smart teen comedy that brings back the dysfunctional 1970s-1980s, when teenagers hadn't yet transmuted into the well-adjusted I-pod generation.

name: The X-Files: I Want to Believe
desc: Scully and Mulder end up in hot pursuit of a maniac who is on the brink of conducting one of the most hair-raising experiments in medical surgery.

name: You Don't Mess With the Zohan
desc: It resolves the Israel-Palestinian conflict with it's schmaltzy love story between the Mossad counter-terrorist, Zohan (Adam Sandler) and the delightful Palestinian hair dresser, Dalia (Emmanuelle Chriqui).

name: Righteous Kill
desc: The magical chemistry is still there as the two veterans play NYPD cops who are trying to nab a psycopath; but age does seem to be catching up with two of Hollywood's greatest.

name: Mamma Mia
desc: The Devil gives up not only her Prada, but also her devilish ways and becomes a singing, dancing angelic muse in this breezy musical that lightens your heart and puts a song to your lips.

name: Padro Nuestro
desc: The film takes you on a journey through New York, like never before, where the glitter has been replaced by the grime; the hope by despair.

name: What Happens in Vegas
desc: This breezy comedy will leave you smiling and grinning with its rib-tickling battle of the sexes that rages on and on.

name: Wall-E
desc: An absolutely delightful futuristic parable, the film carries the Pixar legacy (remember Finding Nemo and Ratatouille?) forward.

name: Wanted
desc: Watch the film for its high-testosterone stunts and action sequences, although Jolie fans might end up somewhat disappointed by this outing.

name: Far North
desc: Two women and a man thrown together in the inhospitable Arctic Tundra can create some compelling drama. Specially since there's a shortage of both food and love.

name: Prom Night
desc: Speaking of prom nights and all the films that feature it Carrie remains the most memorable film, with the tele-kinetic teenager's nightmare still creating a chill amongst film buffs.

name: Sky Fighters
desc: The film keeps the adrenalin pumping with its tale of two fighter pilots, who end up saving Paris on Bastille Day from a bunch of terrorists who have stolen a Mirage and propose to create havoc with the flying machine.

name: Shortcut To Happiness
desc: The effect shows -- Baldwin sells his soul to devil, Jennifer Love Hewitt, lacks the sting of a delightfully devilish tale.

name: The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor
desc: All you Mummy fans need not despair because there's a sequel in store, for the film ends with a teaser pointing to future action in Peru.

name: The Dark Knight
desc: Heath Ledger pitches in a breath-taking performance as Batman's arch rival in Christopher Nolan's breath-taking renditition of the comic book hero's second caper after Batman Begins.

name: Goodbye Bafana
desc: Based on the controversial book by prison guard James Gregory, Goodbye Bafana traces his relationship with Nelson Mandela that covers a span of almost two decades.

name: The Other Boleyn Girl
desc: It's a drama of love, passion and desertion set against the backdrop of the Tudor period, where a brooding King Henry V111 (Eric Bana) is desperate to have a male heir for the throne of England.

name: The Lives of Others
desc: This German film which won the Oscar for Best Foreign film last year and several other international awards is truly a sonata to human goodness.

name: Kung Fu Panda
desc: He's THE Big Fat Panda! True. Salutations to one of the sweetest, funniest animation hero to be seen on the screen, of late.

name: Hancock
desc: It's the season of super heroes in Hollywood. Close on the heels of Iron Man, Indiana Jones and The Incredible Hulk comes Hancock.

name: Caramel
desc: Here's a Lebanese take on Sex and the City which captures the lives of a bunch of women in Beirut, as they struggle to find love and happiness.

name: Made of Honor
desc: The chemistry may be a bit tepid and the plot somewhat tardy and foregone, but there's enough for Dempsey fans to get dreamy about.

name: Charlie Bartlett
desc: Compelling performances by Robert Downey Jr and Anton Yelchin coupled with an undercurrent of comedy make this an interesting film that mirrors high school life with all its highs and lows.

name: Get Smart
desc: Now this one's quite a funny spoof on the James Bond series, in league with Austin Powers' ass-brained mission to save the world.

name: Sex and the City
desc: No, this one's not merely a chick flick. Not with its sassy look at urban relationships and its sane advice: let's not brand relationships and box them into conventions.

name: Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull
desc: It's a great comeback for the quintessential adventurer, Henry Jones Junior (Harrison Ford) who may be 65 years old, but he is still not willing to relinquish his characteristic hat to Henry Jones Junior 11.

name: The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian
desc: Loads of computer-generated wizardry, an edge of teen romance and the usual ode to valour and justice: this second part in C.S. Lewis' seven part fantasy has the requisite thrills.

name: Speed Racer
desc: Speed Racer is a film that breaks all the stereotypes, even though it dabbles with nothing but stereotypes. Don't miss this post-modern pulp fiction.

name: Iron Man
desc: Iron Man may not have been the Big Hero of Marvel Comics, but here, in his first film avtar, he stands as tall as the rest of masked crusaders. Behold! a hero is born.

name: Dr Seuss Horton hears a Who
desc: This one's a sweet little parable on politics with its cutesy diatribe against big worlds swallowing small worlds. Go for it.

name: Juno
desc: Here's a film that tackles a tangled topic -- teen pregnancy -- without getting into knots and tangles. It's such a fresh, uncomplicated look at one of the most compelling problems today.

name: Meet the Spartans
desc: The film chooses to spoof any and everything that has been entertainment news including a bald Britney, Brangelina's adoption bid, Paris Hilton and her pet dog. Too crowded, clumsy and kitchy.

name: D-War
desc: The film blends the occidental and the oriental as it moves between America, here and now, and Korea's Chosun dynasty, 500 years ago.

name: The Bucket List
desc: A sweet, feel good film about death and friendship, The Bucket List is more about kalakars (actors) than kahani (story).

name: The Ex
desc: There's nothing smart about this two-boys-one-girl romance which sorely lacks a comedy track, despite being mounted as a comedy.

name: August Rush
desc: Truly dreamy, with loads of great music and stunning visuals, this is predictable, yet watchable fare. More importantly, it's Charles Dickens, revisited, albeit as a musical.

name: We Own The Night
desc: The predictable script and the formulaic twists and turns reduce the film to a run-of-the-mill, albeit watchable film.

name: 10,000 BC
desc: The story is more exciting to read than to see, for although the canvas is large, the thrills are not larger-than-life.

name: Letters From Iwo Jima
desc: In the end, Letters... is a moving -- and artistic -- indictment of war and violence which should actually have no place in global politics.

name: Vantage Point
desc: The interesting part is the eight versions of the assassination attempt, as the event is told -- and re-told -- through the eyes of the different people who were present there.

name: There Will Be Blood
desc: Watch it for Anderson's eye for detail and for Daniel Day-Lewis who lends grandeur a period charm to Plainview despite his questionable motives.

name: Michael Clayton
desc: The narrative gets somewhat dense, here and there, but leave it to Clooney to carry you through this legal maze that takes a detour into the character's personal hell.

name: The Nanny Diaries
desc: If you loved The Devil Wears Prada, rest assured, you will like this one. Because both the films follow the same storyline.

name: Enchanted
desc: This is crazy, zany and absolutely delightful Disney fare that is determined to light up your evening with its brilliant re-writing of the quintessential fairy tale.

name: August Rush
desc: Truly dreamy, with loads of great music and stunning visuals, this is predictable, yet watchable fare. More importantly, it's Charles Dickens, revisited, albeit as a musical.

name: Turistas
desc: This blood and gore fest, which unfolds either in an underlit house or the dark underwaters of the Brazilian sea shore, is simply barbaric.

name: Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem
desc: It seems like the directors have smartly served up a sci-fi film so that blood could flow, and it does. Unfortunately, it doesn't flow with much imagination.

name: Rambo 4
desc: For all those who got hooked on to Rambo's exploits in First Blood, his Fourth Blood heroics may bring back nostalgic memories of a cold and clinical killing machine.

name: Alvin and the Chipmunks
desc: Like all sweet films, this one too serenades family values as invaluable, transcending money, glamour and the glitzy glutton's life.

name: National Treasure: Book of Secrets
desc: Loads of insipid rummaging through history's memorabilia followed by some uneventful trips to discover a forgotten city of gold don't actually make for a thrilling adventure.

name: Fur
desc: The film has a slow, languorous pace which might put off many, but for those who like a different cinematic experience, Fur could end up as engaging cinema.

name: The Jane Austen Book Club
desc: Go find an Emma, a Darcy in this contemporary homage to Austen's sense and sensibility. A must for all Austen-philes.

name: Nancy Drew Get a Clue
desc: If you've grown up on Nancy Drew stories, the staple fare for post-Enid Blyton, pre-Harold Robbins bookworms, you sure are gonna be disappointed by this one.
The film focuses on the nightmarish experience of a writer who checks into the haunted room to get inspiration for his next bestseller.

name: Bee Movie
desc: Enough to make you sit back and laugh as you watch a stingy little fella called Barry Bee make a beeline for humankind and teach them how to bee-have.

name: Hitman
desc: Hitman is one more game from Playstation to find its way on to the big screen. And like the rest of the kick butt series, this too ends up minus all thrills in its bigger avatar.

name: Beowulf
desc: The ancient English epic poem about a hero comes to life in a state-of-the-art film which is absolutely new, novel and different in terms of technique.

name: Elizabeth, The Golden Age
desc: This one is laboured and has nothing new to offer, other than a power-packed performance by Cate Blanchett who plays the eponymous role with gusto and verve.

name: A Mighty Heart
desc: Winterbottom's take on the Daniel Pearl murder is an edge of the seat thriller that hits hard, and touches your heart.

name: The Contract
desc: The film should have actually been quite average, if it wasn't for Morgan Freeman who adds gravitas to whatever he does.

name: The Bourne Ultimatum
desc: This third film in the Bourne trilogy is a relentless action stunner which doesn't let you sit back for a moment. Go, get your thrills.

name: Blind Dating
desc: There's one big reason why you should watch this film; only one. And that's the fact that we have an Indian playing the heroine to an all-American hero.

name: Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix
Stardust
desc: Here’s a quixotic pariyon ki kahani for adults, laced with delicious fantasy, dreamy landscapes and an allegorical tenor that makes Stardust a watchable parable on love and life.

name: Marigold
desc: A bit more energy and the film could have been a sweet crossover romance. But then, haven’t we seen enough of the half-baked versions of desi-pardesi couplings.

name: The Kingdom
desc: There's nothing new to keep you glued, despite the fact that Jamie Foxx and Chris Cooper are amongst the diehard dependables of Hollywood. Blame it on the unimaginative script.

name: The Simpsons Movie
desc: The film is meant to make you sit back and have fun while America's No.l dysfunctional family sets the world in disorder.

name: The Host
desc: The film is a country cousin of the hi-tech dinos of Spielberg's super thriller. We need to have imports that are quintessentially Korean rather than pale copies of Hollywood.

name: 30 Days of Night
desc: Now if Hollywood wants to make another vampire film, it needs to add something new. No more of those bloody fangs on those ashen faces, please.

name: Resident Evil: Extinction
desc: It’s the third in the Resident Evil franchise which is based on the popular Capcom video game series. And it is the best when compared to the earlier two, Resident Evil and Resident Evil Apocalypse.

name: Rush Hour 3
desc: Prolonged paisa vasool action sequences on the multi-storeyed metal marvel coupled with quirky Tucker humour and cheesy Chan chopsucky could make for mirthful timepass.

name: Premonition
desc: A super-natural thriller, the film could have been a Sixth Sense or a Memento. It isn’t. Instead, it ends up as rather drab.

name: Lions for Lambs
desc: The film is essentially one long conversation, divided into three sequences. Nevertheless, you listen because it is a topical and sensible diatribe against post 9/11 America.

name: Next
desc: It's time to duck bullets and dodge canons, as clairvoyant Cage tries to save the nation and his nymph. Interesting.

name: No Reservations
desc: Watch out for the heart tugging sequences between the little miss Abigail and Zeta-Jones who graduates from imperfect mother to perfect guardian.

name: Because I Said So
desc: The funny parts are laidback, the romantic bits hardly sizzle and the acting isn't much to write about, yet the film strikes a chord.

name: Hannibal Rising
desc: It may not be as rivetting as The Silence of the Lambs, but Hannibal Rising is a gritty fare. Indeed, a strange new world in cinema!

name: Fantastic Four 2: Rise of the Silver Surfer
